Come on.

145
00:09:15,759 --> 00:09:18,023
I don't wanna
live in the back.

146
00:09:18,095 --> 00:09:21,895
Why do we always have
to live in the back?
Shh, honey.

147
00:09:28,439 --> 00:09:31,636
[Whispering]
Thank you, Mr. McKinney.

148
00:09:31,709 --> 00:09:34,701
<i>[Girls Giggling]</i>
Shh. Good-bye.

149
00:09:34,778 --> 00:09:38,714
<i>[Giggling Continues]</i>

150
00:09:38,782 --> 00:09:40,716
Shh!
[Giggling]

151
00:09:53,264 --> 00:09:55,824
Good morning, darling.

152
00:09:55,900 --> 00:09:58,232
Good morning,
Sarah Jane.
I want a kiss too.

153
00:09:58,302 --> 00:10:00,600
Well, of course.

154
00:10:00,671 --> 00:10:03,834
Annie said we had to be quiet
until you got up.

155
00:10:03,908 --> 00:10:06,934
Now we can talk out loud.
Now we can even scream.

156
00:10:07,011 --> 00:10:09,445
- [Screaming]
- Children!

157
00:10:09,513 --> 00:10:11,913
<i>Children! What... </i>

158
00:10:11,982 --> 00:10:14,974
Oh, good morning,
Miss Lora.
<i>Good morning. </i>

159
00:10:15,052 --> 00:10:18,021
How are you
this morning?
<i>Just fine. </i>

160
00:10:18,088 --> 00:10:20,886
I'd love some coffee.

161
00:10:20,958 --> 00:10:24,052
Well, Annie, you shouldn't
have done my laundry.

162
00:10:24,128 --> 00:10:27,325
I like taking care
of pretty things.

163
00:10:27,398 --> 00:10:30,492
Thank you.

164
00:10:30,568 --> 00:10:33,264
Eggs?
Where did they come from?

165
00:10:33,337 --> 00:10:35,601
The milkman was here
a minute ago.

166
00:10:35,673 --> 00:10:37,607
I told him to leave
your regular order.

167
00:10:37,675 --> 00:10:42,135
Oh, no. He didn't come
to leave my order. He stopped
doing that two weeks ago.

168
00:10:42,212 --> 00:10:44,180
May I?
Thank you.

169
00:10:44,248 --> 00:10:46,273
He wanted to collect
something on his bill.

170
00:10:46,350 --> 00:10:49,683
Didn't say anything
about a bill to me.
He was very polite.

171
00:10:49,753 --> 00:10:52,654
Gave me the order and said,
looked like things
were picking up.

172
00:10:52,723 --> 00:10:56,659
He thought you were my maid.
Now he thinks I'm prosperous.

173
00:10:56,727 --> 00:11:00,663
No sin in lookin' prosperous.
Just a way of showin'
your trust in the lord.

174
00:11:00,731 --> 00:11:03,199
Telling him you're ready
whenever he is.

175
00:11:03,267 --> 00:11:05,462
<i>[Phone Ringing]</i>
<i>I'll get it, Miss Lora. </i>

176
00:11:05,536 --> 00:11:08,061
<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>

177
00:11:08,138 --> 00:11:11,335
Miss Meredith's
residence.

178
00:11:11,408 --> 00:11:14,900
I'll see if it's convenient
for Miss Meredith
to come to the phone.

179
00:11:14,979 --> 00:11:17,140
Is it the landlord
Mr. Berwitt?

180
00:11:17,214 --> 00:11:21,150
Pretty sure he said
the A-Acme Model Agency.

181
00:11:23,587 --> 00:11:25,521
Hello?

182
00:11:25,589 --> 00:11:28,752
Yes, this is Miss Meredith.

183
00:11:28,826 --> 00:11:31,192
<i>[Water Running]</i>

184
00:11:31,261 --> 00:11:35,254
Yes. Yes, I can be there
by then.

185
00:11:38,202 --> 00:11:40,898
Fine. Thank you.

186
00:11:40,971 --> 00:11:43,269
Oh, Annie, I've got
a job modeling.

187
00:11:43,340 --> 00:11:44,602
A job?

188
00:11:44,675 --> 00:11:47,109
I've registered everywhere.
But this is the first call.

189
00:11:47,177 --> 00:11:49,236
Now, isn't that fine?

190
00:11:53,784 --> 00:11:58,949
Annie, if you have
no other plans, will you stay
with Susie until I come back?

191
00:11:59,023 --> 00:12:01,082
Why, certainly.

192
00:12:01,158 --> 00:12:04,889
Do you know this will be
the first money I've earned
since I came to New York?

193
00:12:04,962 --> 00:12:07,294
Except for those envelopes.

194
00:12:07,364 --> 00:12:11,061
I was wondering what they were.
<i>I address them</i>
<i>for a mail-order house. </i>

195
00:12:11,135 --> 00:12:15,902
By hand.
It gives them a personal touch,
and I can do them at home.

196
00:12:15,973 --> 00:12:20,637
They should have been
finished yesterday.
Well, can't be helped.

197
00:12:20,711 --> 00:12:23,612
If I get a job modeling,
at least I'll be seen.

198
00:12:23,681 --> 00:12:25,615
<i>[Dog Panting]</i>

199
00:12:31,455 --> 00:12:33,389
Good boy.

200
00:12:33,457 --> 00:12:36,324
Yes, that's fine.
That's what I want.
Hold it. Beautiful.

201
00:12:36,393 --> 00:12:38,327
Just a minute.
Hold it.

202
00:12:38,395 --> 00:12:40,955
<i>[Train Approaching]</i>
[Sneezing]

203
00:12:41,031 --> 00:12:44,660
How could you sneeze?
I had it.

204
00:12:44,735 --> 00:12:46,896
<i>I'm sorry, but it must be</i>
<i>this flea powder. </i>

205
00:12:46,970 --> 00:12:50,701
No, no, no. Don't move.
You'll unfocus me.

206
00:12:50,774 --> 00:12:53,242
Art they want
and I get sneezes.

207
00:12:53,310 --> 00:12:55,972
Now, don't move a hair.
Not one hair.

208
00:12:56,046 --> 00:12:58,207
Hold it, hold it.

209
00:13:03,554 --> 00:13:06,352
Okay.

210
00:13:06,423 --> 00:13:09,085
[Sighing]
Got it. Perfect.

211
00:13:09,159 --> 00:13:11,127
[Sneezing]

212
00:13:11,195 --> 00:13:14,289
You were
wonderful, Henry.
I never sneeze. Really...

213
00:13:14,364 --> 00:13:16,298
Your check will be
in the mail.

214
00:13:16,366 --> 00:13:19,529
It would be so much
more convenient...
Checks are mailed on Thursday.

215
00:13:19,603 --> 00:13:22,003
We don't want to confuse
the bookkeeper.

216
00:13:22,072 --> 00:13:24,131
Don't forget to leave
the wardrobe.

217
00:13:29,012 --> 00:13:31,344
[Imitating Snarl]
[Barks]

218
00:13:33,817 --> 00:13:36,479
But wouldn't you like
to have a bite to eat?

219
00:13:36,553 --> 00:13:38,521
Later. Thanks.

220
00:13:45,796 --> 00:13:49,323
You can keep the money
from this batch, Annie.

221
00:13:49,399 --> 00:13:51,799
It'll pay you for staying
today and cooking and...

222
00:13:51,869 --> 00:13:54,337
Uh-uh. That money
goes into our kitty.

223
00:13:56,073 --> 00:13:59,099
"Our"?

224
00:13:59,176 --> 00:14:01,144
Seems as if
you intend to stay.

225
00:14:01,211 --> 00:14:05,511
Seems like I do,
if, if you want it.

226
00:14:07,618 --> 00:14:11,987
You know I do.
But you can see
how bad things are.

227
00:14:12,055 --> 00:14:17,186
Miss Lora, we just come
from a place where,

228
00:14:17,261 --> 00:14:21,357
where my color
deviled my baby.

229
00:14:21,431 --> 00:14:23,899
Now, anything happens here
has gotta be better.

230
00:14:23,967 --> 00:14:27,664
Oh, Annie.
Oh.

231
00:14:34,311 --> 00:14:38,111
Susie? Susie?
I'm home...

232
00:14:38,182 --> 00:14:41,549
Oh, baby.
Mmm. Hi, dear.

233
00:14:41,618 --> 00:14:43,552
Hello, Miss Lora.
Hello, Annie.

234
00:14:43,620 --> 00:14:47,716
Mommy, we had such fun today.
Annie took us to the park
and we caught a squirrel.

235
00:14:47,791 --> 00:14:51,488
No, we didn't.
Well, we nearly did.

236
00:14:51,562 --> 00:14:55,999
Tomorrow I'll take you
both to the park and
we'll really catch one.

237
00:14:56,066 --> 00:14:59,331
How'd it go?
Oh, Annie.

238
00:15:00,404 --> 00:15:02,338
It didn't.

239
00:15:04,775 --> 00:15:06,902
And I'm exhausted.

240
00:15:06,977 --> 00:15:10,310
Walked my feet off
trying to see every
agent on Broadway.

241
00:15:10,380 --> 00:15:13,213
And some off Broadway.
Way off.

242
00:15:13,283 --> 00:15:15,751
<i>[Buzzer Buzzing]</i>
I'll get it.

243
00:15:15,819 --> 00:15:18,083
The children have eaten.

244
00:15:19,156 --> 00:15:21,716
Yes?
Hello, this is
Steve Archer.

245
00:15:21,792 --> 00:15:24,124
- Steve Archer?
- I brought the pictures.

246
00:15:24,194 --> 00:15:27,789
You brought the pictures?
The ones of the children
on the beach.

247
00:15:27,865 --> 00:15:31,062
Oh, the man on the beach.
<i>[Sarah Jane]</i>
<i>The man on the beach? </i>

248
00:15:31,134 --> 00:15:33,432
The man on the beach!
It's our picture
with the fat man!

249
00:15:33,503 --> 00:15:36,336
<i>Mommy, tell him</i>
<i>to come up. </i>
<i>Yes, please! </i>

250
00:15:36,406 --> 00:15:41,139
Oh, all right. Will
you come up, Mr. Archer?
<i>[Girls Squealing]</i>

251
00:15:41,211 --> 00:15:45,807
<i>[Girls Laughing]</i>

252
00:15:45,883 --> 00:15:50,479
Come on. Let's see.
Did you bring the pictures?
Hi, Susie, Sarah Jane.

253
00:15:50,554 --> 00:15:52,579
Where is it?
Aren't you kids
supposed to be in bed?

254
00:15:52,656 --> 00:15:54,624
No, we waited for you!

255
00:15:54,691 --> 00:15:57,319
[Chuckling]
Hello.
Good evening.

256
00:15:57,394 --> 00:16:01,626
[Squealing, Laughing]

257
00:16:01,698 --> 00:16:05,031
[Laughing]

258
00:16:05,102 --> 00:16:08,435
If it's that funny,
let me see it.

259
00:16:13,644 --> 00:16:17,045
[Laughing]
Don't you think
it's funny, Annie?

260
00:16:17,114 --> 00:16:20,709
<i>[Lora]</i>
<i>I don't know who's funnier, </i>
<i>you or that man. </i>

261
00:16:20,784 --> 00:16:25,346
All I got to say is,
it's lucky I didn't catch
Sarah Jane playing such pranks.

262
00:16:25,422 --> 00:16:28,983
It just ain't
seemly, Miss Lora.
Now, off to bed.

263
00:16:29,059 --> 00:16:31,027
Good night.
Good night.

264
00:16:31,094 --> 00:16:33,358
Good night, Mr. Archer.
Good night, ladies.

265
00:16:33,430 --> 00:16:36,456
Good night.
Won't you sit down?

266
00:16:36,533 --> 00:16:39,502
It was very nice of you
to remember the children.

267
00:16:39,569 --> 00:16:44,006
I like what you did...
for Sarah Jane and Annie.

268
00:16:44,074 --> 00:16:48,738
Well, they didn't have a place
and since I live here alone...

269
00:16:48,812 --> 00:16:53,647
I'm a widow.
Oh, you... are.

270
00:16:56,553 --> 00:16:59,852
What do you think of this?

271
00:16:59,923 --> 00:17:02,050
<i>[Steve]</i>
<i>Mother in distress. </i>

272
00:17:02,125 --> 00:17:05,617
Well, that's good.
Very good.

273
00:17:08,432 --> 00:17:12,528
Who are you anyway?
Well, you don't look
like a photographer.

274
00:17:12,602 --> 00:17:14,934
Apparently the army
thought I did.

275
00:17:15,005 --> 00:17:16,996
Anyhow, they made me one.

276
00:17:17,074 --> 00:17:20,942
Now all I wanna do is
get pictures like this
in The Museum of Modern Art.

277
00:17:21,011 --> 00:17:23,343
Oh, you're aiming high.

278
00:17:23,413 --> 00:17:25,711
Why not?
It doesn't cost anymore.

279
00:17:25,782 --> 00:17:29,013
Don't you believe
in chasing rainbows?

280
00:17:29,086 --> 00:17:34,718
Well, if I didn't,
I wouldn't be here.
I'm an actress.

281
00:17:37,627 --> 00:17:41,620
What's the matter?
Your bones.

282
00:17:41,698 --> 00:17:44,428
What about my bones?

283
00:17:44,501 --> 00:17:46,935
They're perfect.

284
00:17:47,004 --> 00:17:51,270
My camera could easily
have a love affair with you.

285
00:17:53,176 --> 00:17:56,441
Don't you think it's
getting a little late?

286
00:17:58,348 --> 00:18:01,647
I don't suppose you'd like
to have dinner with me.

287
00:18:01,718 --> 00:18:04,380
Maybe. Sometime.

288
00:18:04,454 --> 00:18:07,787
I don't mean right away.
How about tomorrow?

289
00:18:07,858 --> 00:18:12,989
I'm sorry, but I don't like
to miss having dinner with the
children two nights in a row.

290
00:18:13,063 --> 00:18:16,328
I can understand that.
How about lunch?

291
00:18:17,734 --> 00:18:19,793
Lunch?

292
00:18:19,870 --> 00:18:22,668
Would you mind taking me
to Rodney's?

293
00:18:22,739 --> 00:18:25,572
It's a little place
on 45th and 8th.

294
00:18:25,642 --> 00:18:27,610
Unemployed actors
can afford it.

295
00:18:27,677 --> 00:18:30,271
Sort of a poor man's 21.

296
00:18:30,347 --> 00:18:33,805
All right, I'll meet you
there at noon.

297
00:18:36,219 --> 00:18:39,211
Oh, by the way,
the name's Steve.

298
00:18:42,626 --> 00:18:44,890
Everybody in here an actor?
Just about.

299
00:18:44,961 --> 00:18:47,623
So far you're the only one
I really believe.

300
00:18:47,697 --> 00:18:52,259
Thank you. Only so far,
you're the only one
in New York who does.

301
00:18:52,335 --> 00:18:55,327
But someday I'm going to
make them all feel that way.

302
00:18:55,405 --> 00:18:59,933
Aren't you a little late
getting started?
I mean, it's...

303
00:19:00,010 --> 00:19:04,208
Yes, five years late.
That's why every day counts.

304
00:19:04,281 --> 00:19:08,843
Why the five-year lapse?
My husband was
in the theater too.

305
00:19:08,919 --> 00:19:12,150
A director.
A good director.

306
00:19:12,222 --> 00:19:14,850
Everything I know
I owe to him.

307
00:19:14,925 --> 00:19:18,827
It was a small town,
a little theater,
but professional.

308
00:19:18,895 --> 00:19:23,195
When he died,
I had to make a living
doing something else.

309
00:19:23,266 --> 00:19:26,258
I never really wanted
anything but the stage.

310
00:19:26,336 --> 00:19:28,395
Oh, except Susie.

311
00:19:28,472 --> 00:19:31,839
So, it took me five years
to save enough money
to come to New York.

312
00:19:31,908 --> 00:19:33,967
But you did it.
Mm-hmm.

313
00:19:34,044 --> 00:19:37,070
And I'm going to be an
actress, an important one...
<i>[Woman] Lora? </i>

314
00:19:37,147 --> 00:19:39,081
[Woman]
Lora.
Oh, excuse me.

315
00:19:39,149 --> 00:19:41,447
Nothing in it for me,
honey,

316
00:19:41,518 --> 00:19:44,885
but they're
beginning to cast a new
Tennessee Williams play.

317
00:19:44,955 --> 00:19:47,890
Oh, what agent?
Allen Loomis... today.

318
00:19:47,958 --> 00:19:50,791
So put on
your roller skates.
Oh, thanks, Fay.

319
00:19:51,928 --> 00:19:53,862
Coffee?
I'm sorry,
but I've got to go.

320
00:19:53,930 --> 00:19:55,864
You haven't eaten.
You go ahead.
Good-bye.

321
00:19:55,932 --> 00:19:57,866
How about dinner?
Tonight?
We'll take Susie.

322
00:19:57,934 --> 00:19:59,902
Fine.
Where?

323
00:19:59,970 --> 00:20:01,938
Come and have
dinner with us.
All right.

324
00:20:02,005 --> 00:20:03,939
Good luck.
Thanks, Fay.

325
00:20:12,448 --> 00:20:15,781
But when can I have
an appointment?

326
00:20:15,852 --> 00:20:20,619
[Sighing]
How about a week
from today? Thursday.

327
00:20:20,690 --> 00:20:25,218
Put me down.
It's Iris Dawn.
Don't forget it.

328
00:20:25,294 --> 00:20:27,228
Tsk.

329
00:20:27,296 --> 00:20:29,696
I'm sorry to add
to your troubles, but...

330
00:20:29,765 --> 00:20:32,359
I'm afraid I'm a little late
for my appointment.

331
00:20:32,435 --> 00:20:35,632
Name, please.
Miss Meredith.

332
00:20:35,705 --> 00:20:38,003
Mered...
Meredith.

333
00:20:38,074 --> 00:20:40,042
Well, I don't seem
to have you down.

334
00:20:40,109 --> 00:20:43,203
Never mind.
Just tell Mr. Loomis
that Robert Hayes sent me.

335
00:20:43,279 --> 00:20:46,680
Robert Hayes?
<i>From International</i>
<i>Studio. </i>

336
00:20:46,749 --> 00:20:50,150
It's probably just a slipup
from the coast, but, uh,

337
00:20:50,219 --> 00:20:52,153
Mr. Hayes won't
like it at all.

338
00:20:52,221 --> 00:20:54,883
<i>I hope you didn't</i>
<i>slip up. </i>
Me?

339
00:20:54,957 --> 00:20:58,586
Well, if you say
there's no appointment,
um, good-bye.

340
00:20:58,661 --> 00:21:00,720
Well, just a second.

341
00:21:00,796 --> 00:21:05,233
Why don't you sit down
and I'll see if I can
straighten this out?

342
00:21:05,301 --> 00:21:07,496
Thank you.

343
00:21:07,570 --> 00:21:09,504
Mr. Loomis?
Yes?

344
00:21:09,572 --> 00:21:11,665
There's a Miss Meredith here
from Hollywood.

345
00:21:11,741 --> 00:21:15,268
<i>[Receptionist Whispering]</i>
<i>Yes, quite lovely. </i>

346
00:21:15,344 --> 00:21:19,747
Think we should
send her away?
No. I think
you ought to see her.

347
00:21:19,815 --> 00:21:22,409
Fine.
Okay.

348
00:21:23,986 --> 00:21:27,888
Miss Meredith?
You can go in now.

349
00:21:32,128 --> 00:21:35,222
Um, just right in.

350
00:21:35,298 --> 00:21:37,357
Robert sends
his warmest greetings.

351
00:21:37,433 --> 00:21:40,800
Well, thanks.
And how is he?
Marvelous.

352
00:21:40,870 --> 00:21:44,328
He's lost 15 pounds.
You know what an effort
that is for him.

353
00:21:44,407 --> 00:21:46,875
And, uh, what can
I do for you?

354
00:21:46,943 --> 00:21:52,006
Robert thought I shouldn't
do any more pictures before
I did a show on Broadway.

355
00:21:52,081 --> 00:21:54,208
Very sensible.
<i>I'm glad</i>
<i>you think so too. </i>

356
00:21:54,283 --> 00:21:58,617
That's why Robert
sent me to you.
He thought I'd get more...

357
00:21:58,688 --> 00:22:01,555
personal attention
from you.

358
00:22:01,624 --> 00:22:04,889
He could be right there.
You mind?
<i>No. </i>

359
00:22:04,961 --> 00:22:07,555
Incidentally, how's the new
Tennessee Williams play?

360
00:22:07,630 --> 00:22:13,034
Bound to be a blockbuster,
but all cast.
<i>[Buzzer Buzzing]</i>

361
00:22:13,102 --> 00:22:16,833
Hello? Oh, Lillian!
What?

362
00:22:16,906 --> 00:22:20,069
<i>Oh, well, </i>
<i>can't you break it? </i>

363
00:22:20,142 --> 00:22:22,610
<i>Oh. No, I don't mind. </i>

364
00:22:22,678 --> 00:22:26,808
I don't mind you
standing me up. I'm fine.
I'll just kill myself.

365
00:22:26,882 --> 00:22:28,816
Yeah.

366
00:22:28,884 --> 00:22:34,151
<i>Never be a bachelor. </i>
<i>There's no security. </i>
I know how you feel.

367
00:22:34,223 --> 00:22:37,659
Yeah? Say, how'd you like
to go with me tonight?

368
00:22:37,727 --> 00:22:40,161
I'm afraid I can't.

369
00:22:40,229 --> 00:22:42,322
Big party.
Lots of important people.

370
00:22:42,398 --> 00:22:47,131
Well, I could see if I could
break a couple of engagements.

371
00:22:47,203 --> 00:22:49,137
I'll call my place.

372
00:22:49,205 --> 00:22:51,469
I'll call.
What's the number?

373
00:22:51,540 --> 00:22:54,236
Montgomery,

374
00:22:54,310 --> 00:22:56,278
76120.

375
00:22:56,345 --> 00:22:59,473
...One, two, oh.

376
00:22:59,548 --> 00:23:02,449
<i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

377
00:23:02,518 --> 00:23:04,816
Miss Meredith's residence.

378
00:23:04,887 --> 00:23:07,617
Oh, this <i>is</i>
Miss Meredith's residence?

379
00:23:07,690 --> 00:23:11,456
That'll be Annie, my maid.
I'll talk to her.

380
00:23:15,931 --> 00:23:20,493
Annie, uh, call
the Waldorf and tell, um,

381
00:23:20,569 --> 00:23:23,800
you-know-who I cannot have
cocktails and dinner with him.

382
00:23:23,873 --> 00:23:28,503
Uh, I know who?
Oh, yes, Miss Lora,
I'll do that.

383
00:23:28,577 --> 00:23:31,045
Thank you.

384
00:23:31,113 --> 00:23:33,138
Well, Mr. Loomis,
it looks like I'm free.

385
00:23:33,215 --> 00:23:36,480
That'll be just fine.
Should be an interesting
evening for me.

386
00:23:36,552 --> 00:23:40,488
Hollywood actress and...
Oh, that reminds me.
Excuse me.

387
00:23:40,556 --> 00:23:42,490
<i>[Button Clicking]</i>
<i>[Receptionist]</i>
<i>Yes, Mr. Loomis? </i>

388
00:23:42,558 --> 00:23:45,118
Annette, get me Hollywood,
Mr. Robert Hayes.

389
00:23:45,194 --> 00:23:49,130
International Studios,
right? International...
Um.

390
00:23:49,198 --> 00:23:52,565
Maybe you better not
go through with that call.

391
00:23:52,635 --> 00:23:55,763
You don't think so?
Why not?

392
00:23:55,838 --> 00:23:57,829
[Sighing]

393
00:23:57,907 --> 00:24:00,967
Because Robert Hayes
doesn't exist.

394
00:24:01,043 --> 00:24:05,537
I understand.
Annette, cancel the call.

395
00:24:05,614 --> 00:24:07,548
<i>Yes, Mr. Loomis. </i>
I was desperate.

396
00:24:07,616 --> 00:24:11,552
You were pretty good.
You lied. All actresses lie.
I know that.

397
00:24:11,620 --> 00:24:14,646
But I believed you.
I'm sorry.

398
00:24:14,723 --> 00:24:18,022
Don't leave.
You took me in.

399
00:24:18,094 --> 00:24:21,029
For all of 20 seconds,
you took me in,
but I don't mind.

400
00:24:21,097 --> 00:24:25,431
It was a good acting job,
and you're very pretty.

401
00:24:25,501 --> 00:24:28,061
Now, about tonight.
Shall I pick you up?

402
00:24:28,137 --> 00:24:31,698
Um, no, it'll be easier
for me to meet you here.

403
00:24:31,774 --> 00:24:35,835
8:00?
You'll find me
very prompt, Mr. Loomis.

404
00:24:50,926 --> 00:24:54,259
[Gate Thumping]

405
00:24:59,568 --> 00:25:01,502
Come on in.

406
00:25:01,570 --> 00:25:05,597
Sit down. I just have
a few letters to sign.

407
00:25:05,674 --> 00:25:07,835
Oh, drink?
No, thank you.

408
00:25:07,910 --> 00:25:12,210
But aren't we going
to be late to the party?
Plenty of time, plenty.

409
00:25:12,281 --> 00:25:15,910
And I need a drink.
So relax.

410
00:25:15,985 --> 00:25:19,079
<i>Say, you're not allergic</i>
<i>to mink, are you? </i>

411
00:25:19,155 --> 00:25:22,852
Mink? No,
I don't think so.
<i>Good. </i>

412
00:25:28,631 --> 00:25:31,862
Try this on for size.

413
00:25:31,934 --> 00:25:35,426
But whose is it?
Mine. And I only loan it
to very special clients.

414
00:25:35,504 --> 00:25:37,699
I want you to wear it
tonight.
You want me to wear...

415
00:25:37,773 --> 00:25:39,707
Please. Got to think
of my reputation.

416
00:25:39,775 --> 00:25:43,711
I haven't been seen
with a girl without a mink
since the heat wave of'39.

417
00:25:43,779 --> 00:25:46,179
Come on.

418
00:25:46,248 --> 00:25:49,547
We should spend
a little time talking
about our future.

419
00:25:49,618 --> 00:25:52,985
You can act. Well,
that's of no importance
at the moment.

420
00:25:53,055 --> 00:25:55,888
The main thing is,
you're a beaut.

421
00:25:55,958 --> 00:26:00,019
Please, don't.
Oh, and you're decent too.

422
00:26:00,095 --> 00:26:02,063
No doubt possess
some fine principles.

423
00:26:02,131 --> 00:26:04,395
Well, me, I'm a man
of very few principles,

424
00:26:04,466 --> 00:26:06,900
and they're all open
to revision.

425
00:26:06,969 --> 00:26:09,494
But I'm in a position
to do something for you.

426
00:26:09,572 --> 00:26:12,564
You'll get 10% of everything
I make. Isn't that enough?

427
00:26:12,641 --> 00:26:15,132
No. Now,
sit down and listen.

428
00:26:16,946 --> 00:26:21,883
Here it is, short and clear.
You're not a chicken.

429
00:26:21,951 --> 00:26:23,942
You're no high-hearted kid
out of some drama school,

430
00:26:24,019 --> 00:26:26,078
wanting to do or die
for dear old Thespis.

431
00:26:26,155 --> 00:26:28,146
<i>And you're beginning</i>
<i>under a handicap. </i>

432
00:26:28,224 --> 00:26:31,057
I know I'm starting late.
<i>So time isn't on your side. </i>

433
00:26:31,126 --> 00:26:33,594
But you do have
some qualifications.

434
00:26:33,662 --> 00:26:37,962
Your face will pass.
You've good, nice, long
silky legs. I like them.

435
00:26:38,033 --> 00:26:40,524
You have a chest full
of quality and quantity.
I like it.

436
00:26:40,603 --> 00:26:44,801
Aren't you taking
a few things for granted?
Me? I don't count.

437
00:26:44,873 --> 00:26:47,808
But there are certain
people who do, and you're
going to meet all of them.

438
00:26:47,876 --> 00:26:50,811
That is, if you're really
serious about your career.

439
00:26:50,879 --> 00:26:54,440
I am, but...
Good, then you're going
every place with me.

440
00:26:54,516 --> 00:26:57,280
Every party, opening night,
every saloon in town.

441
00:26:57,353 --> 00:27:00,322
With a complete new
wardrobe at my expense.

442
00:27:00,389 --> 00:27:02,289
Oh, it's tax deductible.

443
00:27:02,358 --> 00:27:04,918
This is a tough,
competitive racket.

444
00:27:04,994 --> 00:27:07,929
Although it's a lot
more than any agent
is supposed to do,

445
00:27:07,997 --> 00:27:11,228
I'd do it.
<i>[Hand Patting Leg]</i>

446
00:27:11,300 --> 00:27:13,393
What's this got
to do with acting?
Nothing.

447
00:27:13,469 --> 00:27:17,269
But I'll show you how to
realize your ambitions,
if you do as I say.

448
00:27:17,339 --> 00:27:20,934
If the dramatists' club wants
to eat and sleep with you,
you eat and sleep with them.

449
00:27:21,010 --> 00:27:24,138
If some producer with a hand
as cold as a toad wants to do
a painting of you in the nude,

450
00:27:24,213 --> 00:27:26,147
you'll accommodate him
for a very small part.

451
00:27:26,215 --> 00:27:28,547
It's disgusting!
It pays off.

452
00:27:28,617 --> 00:27:30,551
You're disgusting.
Maybe I am.

453
00:27:30,619 --> 00:27:34,555
But let me assure you,
once you get it made,

454
00:27:34,623 --> 00:27:37,490
you can be idealistic
all of ten seconds
before you die.

455
00:27:37,559 --> 00:27:41,427
You're trying to cheapen me.
But you won't. Not me.

456
00:27:41,497 --> 00:27:44,898
Oh, I'll make it, Mr. Loomis,
but it'll be my way.

457
00:27:55,176 --> 00:27:57,610
You have a wonderful
handwriting, Annie.

458
00:27:57,679 --> 00:28:01,513
Oh, thank you, Mr. Steve.
But my spellin'
won't take no prizes.

459
00:28:01,583 --> 00:28:04,211
I don't think Lora
has anything to worry about
as long as you're with her.

460
00:28:04,285 --> 00:28:07,584
Oh, we'll get by.
I made an agreement
with the landlord.

461
00:28:07,655 --> 00:28:09,748
He's really
a nice person.
Oh?

462
00:28:09,824 --> 00:28:13,260
Just for doin'
the staircases twice a week,
we get $10 off our rent.

463
00:28:13,328 --> 00:28:15,262
Is that a fact?

464
00:28:15,330 --> 00:28:18,299
I answered an ad
and got a job while
the kids are at school.

465
00:28:18,366 --> 00:28:20,994
Doing what?
Doing shirts
for a gentleman.

466
00:28:21,069 --> 00:28:24,470
He's real persnickety
about his shirts.
<i>[Door Opening]</i>

467
00:28:45,860 --> 00:28:48,693
Oh, Steve.
Hello.

468
00:28:48,763 --> 00:28:51,823
I'm sorry. It's just
that I got so involved.

469
00:28:51,900 --> 00:28:55,233
We're having
a wonderful time.
How'd everything go?

470
00:28:55,303 --> 00:28:59,262
Oh, just fine. I went
to the 21 with Mr. Loomis.

471
00:28:59,340 --> 00:29:02,036
Everybody there
was somebody exciting.

472
00:29:02,110 --> 00:29:04,806
For the first time,
I felt that I was somebody too.

473
00:29:04,879 --> 00:29:06,904
Is Mr. Loomis gonna
find you a job?

474
00:29:06,981 --> 00:29:10,212
Well, he, uh,

475
00:29:10,285 --> 00:29:13,584
he wanted to represent me,
but...

476
00:29:17,058 --> 00:29:20,516
But l...
Oh, Annie.

477
00:29:20,595 --> 00:29:23,587
What's wrong, Miss Lora?
[Crying]

478
00:29:23,665 --> 00:29:27,192
Everything. Everything.

479
00:29:27,268 --> 00:29:32,638
Now, you just rest.
Everything will work out.

480
00:29:32,707 --> 00:29:37,041
I'll go get you
a glass of hot milk, huh?

481
00:29:46,054 --> 00:29:49,182
Can I help in any way?
No.

482
00:29:49,257 --> 00:29:52,158
No one can.

483
00:29:52,226 --> 00:29:54,626
No one.

484
00:29:54,696 --> 00:29:57,358
I'm so ashamed.

485
00:29:58,733 --> 00:30:01,861
It was horrible.

486
00:30:01,936 --> 00:30:04,962
He tried to make me
feel so cheap.

487
00:30:05,039 --> 00:30:06,973
You could never
be cheap.

488
00:30:07,041 --> 00:30:10,499
You don't know
what I mean.
Yes, I do.

489
00:30:10,578 --> 00:30:13,911
It happens all the time.
Not just in the theater.

490
00:30:13,982 --> 00:30:16,883
I love the theater.
It's what I want.

491
00:30:16,951 --> 00:30:21,217
Then hold onto your dreams.
Forget tonight.

492
00:30:21,289 --> 00:30:25,589
But they seem so stale
after tonight.

493
00:30:25,660 --> 00:30:30,688
So stale I can't believe
in them anymore.

494
00:30:30,765 --> 00:30:34,098
M-Maybe I'm a fool.

495
00:30:35,837 --> 00:30:39,603
Maybe I should see things
as they really are...

496
00:30:39,674 --> 00:30:43,542
and not as
I want them to be.

497
00:30:43,611 --> 00:30:48,378
If I know you,
they'll have to be
the way you want them.

498
00:30:50,685 --> 00:30:52,915
Thanks, Steve.

499
00:30:52,987 --> 00:30:58,220
You're so, so good
for what ails me.

500
00:30:58,292 --> 00:31:03,195
It's all part of
the Archer service...
day or night.

501
00:31:04,265 --> 00:31:07,564
I'll call you soon,
Lora.

502
00:31:07,635 --> 00:31:09,603
Tomorrow.

503
00:31:09,670 --> 00:31:11,604
Yes, please, tomorrow.

504
00:31:37,365 --> 00:31:41,461
<i>Annie, what's happened</i>
<i>to Susie's wrist? </i>

505
00:31:41,536 --> 00:31:45,666
Oh, nothin' serious.
Just a little experiment.

506
00:31:45,740 --> 00:31:47,970
Experiment?
Sarah Jane's fault.

507
00:31:48,042 --> 00:31:52,570
After class, one of the kids
said that Negro blood
was different.

508
00:31:52,647 --> 00:31:56,674
So later this evenin',
Sarah Jane wanted to compare
her blood with Susie's.

509
00:31:56,751 --> 00:31:59,345
Well, I spanked her good.

510
00:31:59,420 --> 00:32:03,015
Oh, well, you know
how children are.

511
00:32:03,091 --> 00:32:05,855
They were only playing.

512
00:32:05,927 --> 00:32:09,863
I hope so, Miss Lora.
I hope so.

513
00:32:16,566 --> 00:32:20,434
Santa Claus has many names
in many different countries.

514
00:32:20,503 --> 00:32:22,937
In Holland, he is
called <i>Sinter Klaas. </i>

515
00:32:23,006 --> 00:32:27,067
<i>In France, </i>
Saint Nicolas.

516
00:32:27,143 --> 00:32:29,543
In Sweden, he is
known as <i>Jul Tomte. </i>

517
00:32:29,613 --> 00:32:33,071
In Germany, he is...
<i>[Knocking]</i>

518
00:32:35,452 --> 00:32:37,420
Oh, can I do something
for you?

519
00:32:37,487 --> 00:32:39,819
<i>Sorry to trouble you, </i>
<i>but I brought these</i>
<i>for my little girl. </i>

520
00:32:39,889 --> 00:32:41,982
I'm afraid you've
made a mistake.

521
00:32:42,058 --> 00:32:43,992
I don't have any little
colored girl in my class.

522
00:32:44,060 --> 00:32:46,790
But they said 3-B.
This is 3-B, isn't...

523
00:32:47,831 --> 00:32:50,322
Why, there's Sarah Jane.

524
00:32:50,400 --> 00:32:53,301
There's my baby.
You mean Sarah Jane
Johnson?

525
00:32:53,370 --> 00:32:56,168
Yes, ma'am.
I'm Mrs. Johnson.

526
00:33:00,777 --> 00:33:04,838
Sarah Jane, baby,
I brought you your...

527
00:33:06,516 --> 00:33:08,848
Sarah Jane!
We didn't know.

528
00:33:10,186 --> 00:33:13,747
<i>Sarah Jane? </i>
<i>Wait. </i>

529
00:33:13,823 --> 00:33:16,383
<i>Sarah Jane? </i>

530
00:33:16,459 --> 00:33:19,053
Baby? Wait.

531
00:33:22,132 --> 00:33:24,498
Sarah Jane?

532
00:33:26,469 --> 00:33:29,233
Sarah Jane, wait.

533
00:33:29,306 --> 00:33:34,300
Wait. Now, now,
let me do it.

534
00:33:34,377 --> 00:33:37,904
Now, put your coat on.
What do you want to do,
catch pneumonia?

535
00:33:37,981 --> 00:33:41,178
I hope I do!
I hope I die!

536
00:33:41,251 --> 00:33:43,276
Honey, nothing's hurt.
You shouldn't
have let them...

537
00:33:43,353 --> 00:33:46,652
They didn't ask me.
Why should I tell them?

538
00:33:46,723 --> 00:33:49,317
Because that's what you
are, and it's nothin'
to be ashamed of.

539
00:33:49,392 --> 00:33:53,328
Why do you have to be
my mother? Why?

540
00:33:59,302 --> 00:34:03,204
Why, you're
practically normal.
[Giggling]

541
00:34:03,273 --> 00:34:05,935
<i>[Door Opening]</i>

542
00:34:19,989 --> 00:34:23,720
You two are soaking wet.
Get out of those things
and I'll make some tea.

543
00:34:23,793 --> 00:34:27,092
I'll be fine.
You better get ready.
Mr. Steve's comin'.

544
00:34:27,163 --> 00:34:31,031
Serve him right to wait.
He was due here
over an hour ago.

545
00:34:31,101 --> 00:34:35,936
I just don't want
everybody having colds.
Cups and...

546
00:34:36,005 --> 00:34:39,270
What's wrong?

547
00:34:39,342 --> 00:34:42,800
Sarah Jane's been
passing at school,

548
00:34:42,879 --> 00:34:44,870
pretending she's white.

549
00:34:44,948 --> 00:34:48,145
But I am white!
I'm as white as Susie.

550
00:34:51,855 --> 00:34:57,350
Oh, honey,
don't you see it doesn't
make any difference to us?

551
00:34:57,427 --> 00:35:01,158
Because we all love you.

552
00:35:01,231 --> 00:35:03,131
I'll take you back
to school myself.

553
00:35:03,199 --> 00:35:05,190
I'm never going back
to that school!

554
00:35:05,268 --> 00:35:08,999
Never as long as I live!

555
00:35:09,072 --> 00:35:12,872
<i>[Door Slamming]</i>
Sarah Jane!
Don't cry!

556
00:35:15,078 --> 00:35:18,741
Annie, don't be upset.
Children are always pretending.

557
00:35:18,815 --> 00:35:21,249
You know that.

558
00:35:21,317 --> 00:35:27,153
No, it's a sin to be
ashamed of what you are.

559
00:35:27,223 --> 00:35:30,556
It's even worse to pretend,

560
00:35:30,627 --> 00:35:32,891
to lie.

561
00:35:32,962 --> 00:35:37,490
Sarah Jane has to learn
that the Lord must
have had his reasons...

562
00:35:37,567 --> 00:35:39,762
for making some
of us white...

563
00:35:39,836 --> 00:35:41,861
and some of us black.

564
00:35:41,938 --> 00:35:43,929
Sarah Jane Doesn't
want me with her.

565
00:35:44,007 --> 00:35:47,568
She says I'm not her friend.
She says nobody's
her friend.

566
00:35:47,644 --> 00:35:51,239
Darling, she's upset right now.
But she'll be better soon.

567
00:35:51,314 --> 00:35:54,647
So will you if you get
back in bed. Come on.

568
00:35:57,420 --> 00:36:01,857
Don't worry, Annie.
I'm sure you'll be able
to explain things to her.

569
00:36:01,925 --> 00:36:05,088
I don't know.

570
00:36:05,161 --> 00:36:10,224
How do you explain to your child
she was born to be hurt?

571
00:36:20,709 --> 00:36:23,769
<i>[Buzzer Buzzing]</i>

572
00:36:25,347 --> 00:36:27,679
Hello.
Hi. Sorry I'm late.

573
00:36:27,750 --> 00:36:32,084
That's all right.
I'm ready. I thought
you'd never get here.

574
00:36:36,325 --> 00:36:38,316
Why, Steve, you sold it!

575
00:36:38,394 --> 00:36:42,353
More than that, they gave me
a job, a steady one
on the advertising staff.

576
00:36:42,431 --> 00:36:44,763
Oh, that's wonderful.

577
00:36:44,833 --> 00:36:48,667
But, darling, is it really
what you want?

578
00:36:48,737 --> 00:36:51,035
Well, it's not
The Museum of Modern Art.

579
00:36:51,106 --> 00:36:54,735
But they pay you
in the nicest-looking
green folding money.

580
00:36:54,810 --> 00:36:57,745
Which reminds me,
this is the season
for spending it.

581
00:36:57,813 --> 00:37:00,247
Let's go.

582
00:37:00,315 --> 00:37:03,944
We have to get a tree,
and I have a list of gifts
for the kids and Annie.

583
00:37:04,019 --> 00:37:06,954
And I hope you like
what I picked out for you.

584
00:37:07,022 --> 00:37:10,355
Oh, Steve, you...
You have to have something
to put under a tree, don't you?

585
00:37:10,426 --> 00:37:12,587
Well, I know, but...
This way, ma'am.

586
00:37:12,661 --> 00:37:14,925
Oh, I feel awful.

587
00:37:14,997 --> 00:37:18,228
I haven't been able to buy
you anything really nice.

588
00:37:18,300 --> 00:37:21,098
It's been five months
without a job...

589
00:37:21,170 --> 00:37:24,936
Then I guess you'll
have to marry me.

590
00:37:25,007 --> 00:37:28,534
It's the least you can do
for me for Christmas.

591
00:37:28,610 --> 00:37:30,703
I love you.

592
00:37:30,779 --> 00:37:33,441
But, darling, you're...

593
00:37:33,515 --> 00:37:36,609
You're just
getting started and...

594
00:37:36,685 --> 00:37:38,619
It would be foolish.

595
00:37:38,687 --> 00:37:41,178
At least we'd
be foolish together.

596
00:37:41,256 --> 00:37:44,123
But marriage
is such a big step.

597
00:37:44,193 --> 00:37:47,890
I want us to be together.
Well, we are,
most of the time.

598
00:37:47,963 --> 00:37:50,591
Most of the time
you're out fighting
to get somewhere.

599
00:37:50,666 --> 00:37:52,634
Breaking your heart,
trying to do for
yourself and Susie...

600
00:37:52,701 --> 00:37:55,226
what I want to do for you,
what I finally
can do for you.

601
00:37:55,304 --> 00:37:58,705
Pardon me. I'm sorry.
Pardon me.
Oh!

602
00:37:58,774 --> 00:38:01,299
Well, wait a minute.

603
00:38:02,878 --> 00:38:07,474
I want to give you a home,
take care of you, love you.

604
00:38:07,549 --> 00:38:11,883
Oh, Steve, you
don't know me at all.

605
00:38:11,954 --> 00:38:14,149
I still love the theater.

606
00:38:14,223 --> 00:38:16,919
You tried it
and it's only hurt you.

607
00:38:16,992 --> 00:38:18,926
Realize that
and you'll get over it.

608
00:38:18,994 --> 00:38:22,725
I want to be honest
with you, darling.

609
00:38:22,798 --> 00:38:25,460
I want more.

610
00:38:25,534 --> 00:38:28,833
Everything.

611
00:38:28,904 --> 00:38:30,838
Maybe too much.

612
00:38:30,906 --> 00:38:33,500
Don't think I want any less.

613
00:38:33,575 --> 00:38:37,272
So let's settle something
right now. Do you love me?

614
00:38:39,248 --> 00:38:41,614
I think I do,
but...

615
00:38:41,683 --> 00:38:43,617
<i>[Door Opening]</i>

616
00:38:43,685 --> 00:38:45,619
Come here.

617
00:38:45,687 --> 00:38:47,985
I want to kiss you
so badly.

618
00:38:48,056 --> 00:38:52,789
But if you did,
the way things are right now,

619
00:38:52,861 --> 00:38:57,321
I might say something
I wouldn't really mean.

620
00:38:57,399 --> 00:39:01,529
That's why
I want to kiss you.
<i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

621
00:39:01,603 --> 00:39:04,003
That's my phone.

622
00:39:04,072 --> 00:39:06,267
<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>

623
00:39:06,341 --> 00:39:09,868
Hello?
Miss Meredith's residence.

624
00:39:10,546 --> 00:39:14,846
- Who, Mr. Loomis?
- She's not in.

625
00:39:14,917 --> 00:39:18,819
She isn't in, Mr. Loomis.
No, not even if it's important.

626
00:39:19,888 --> 00:39:21,822
<i>[Annie]</i>
<i>What? A job? </i>

627
00:39:21,890 --> 00:39:25,326
l... I have to find out.
It could be something.

628
00:39:28,397 --> 00:39:30,331
Yes, Mr. Loomis?

629
00:39:30,399 --> 00:39:33,800
You look good with
a St. Bernard dog.
The St. Bernard dog?

630
00:39:33,869 --> 00:39:35,803
Yes. Uh-huh.

631
00:39:35,871 --> 00:39:38,806
Well, that's you
in the picture, isn't it?

632
00:39:38,874 --> 00:39:41,308
Sprinkling flea powder?

633
00:39:41,376 --> 00:39:43,844
All right, well, I'm here
with David Edwards.

634
00:39:43,912 --> 00:39:45,777
David...
Edwards, yes.

635
00:39:45,848 --> 00:39:48,180
You know,
the prize-winning playwright.

636
00:39:48,250 --> 00:39:50,684
He saw that picture
in a magazine.

637
00:39:50,752 --> 00:39:54,688
He's looking for a girl with
that certain <i>je ne sais quoi</i>
for his new play.

638
00:39:54,756 --> 00:39:58,021
That certain something
you managed to get
with the dog.

639
00:39:58,093 --> 00:40:01,995
It's not a big part, I know...
If this is one of
your jokes, Mr. Loomis...

640
00:40:02,064 --> 00:40:04,999
Jokes? So help me,
I'm only thinking
percentage-wise.

641
00:40:05,067 --> 00:40:07,501
The part calls for
about...
Two and a half.

642
00:40:07,569 --> 00:40:10,003
Two-fifty a week.

643
00:40:10,072 --> 00:40:13,405
I left the script with
my secretary. Can you
pick it up immediately?

644
00:40:13,475 --> 00:40:15,966
Uh, yes.
Yes, Mr. Loomis.

645
00:40:16,044 --> 00:40:17,978
Yes.

646
00:40:18,046 --> 00:40:20,981
He wants me
to pick up a script;
I'm to audition tomorrow.

647
00:40:21,049 --> 00:40:22,983
And you're going
down there?
Of course.

648
00:40:23,051 --> 00:40:26,487
Even after what
happened last time?
This has
nothing to do with Loomis.

649
00:40:26,555 --> 00:40:29,991
I'm to audition
for David Edwards.
How do you know that?

650
00:40:30,058 --> 00:40:31,992
I know. I just know.

651
00:40:32,060 --> 00:40:35,996
But do you know if he's
gonna be any different
than Loomis?
No, I don't.

652
00:40:36,064 --> 00:40:40,524
I don't want you to go.
Don't you realize what
this could mean to me?

653
00:40:40,602 --> 00:40:44,038
I'm not asking you
not to go down there,
I'm <i>telling</i> you.

654
00:40:44,106 --> 00:40:47,542
What makes you think
you have that right?
Because I love you.

655
00:40:47,609 --> 00:40:50,544
Isn't that enough?
No, Steve, I'm sorry.
Good night.

656
00:40:52,014 --> 00:40:54,812
Lora, wait.

657
00:40:54,883 --> 00:40:58,319
I didn't mean
to sound dictatorial or
to try to run your life,

658
00:40:58,387 --> 00:41:01,823
but you have to understand
how I feel.
And what about
the way I feel?

659
00:41:01,890 --> 00:41:04,256
Oh, stop acting.
I'm not acting.

660
00:41:04,326 --> 00:41:07,261
I want to achieve something,
something you'll never
understand.

661
00:41:07,329 --> 00:41:10,821
What you're after isn't real.
At least
I'm after something!

662
00:41:10,899 --> 00:41:14,335
Not the snapshot of
a disgusting old man with
a beer can on his belly.

663
00:41:14,403 --> 00:41:17,839
Is that your idea
of achieving something?
Is a beer can "real"?

664
00:41:17,906 --> 00:41:19,840
Going up and down,
up and down.

665
00:41:19,908 --> 00:41:23,344
Well, I'm going up and up
and up, and nobody's
going to pull me down!

666
00:41:23,412 --> 00:41:25,607
Lora, listen, please.

667
00:41:25,681 --> 00:41:29,117
I've been trying to do
something with my pictures.
It's meant everything to me.

668
00:41:29,184 --> 00:41:32,119
Every minute,
for a long time now.
No, it hasn't.

669
00:41:32,187 --> 00:41:35,315
Or you wouldn't
give it up to sell beer.

670
00:41:35,390 --> 00:41:39,326
I gave it up for
something much better,
something right now: You.

671
00:41:39,394 --> 00:41:42,830
But you're asking me
to give up something
I've wanted all my life,

672
00:41:42,898 --> 00:41:45,833
ever since I was a child,
and I can't do it!

673
00:41:45,901 --> 00:41:47,835
If you grew up,
you could.

674
00:41:49,237 --> 00:41:51,171
What do you mean?

675
00:41:52,374 --> 00:41:54,308
You're not
a child anymore,

676
00:41:54,376 --> 00:41:57,311
and I might not be around
to pick up the pieces
this time.

677
00:41:57,379 --> 00:41:59,313
Good.

678
00:41:59,381 --> 00:42:02,111
I'd like it that way.
Forever.

679
00:42:17,933 --> 00:42:21,869
Joseph and Mary couldn't
find no place at the inn,

680
00:42:21,937 --> 00:42:25,373
so they had to go to the
stable among the animals.

681
00:42:25,440 --> 00:42:27,374
The animals?
Mm-hmm.

682
00:42:27,442 --> 00:42:30,377
And in the manger
Jesus was born.

683
00:42:30,445 --> 00:42:34,040
<i>And the heavenly hosts</i>
<i>sang, "Hallelujah. "</i>

684
00:42:34,116 --> 00:42:37,051
<i>There was a shining bright</i>
<i>star in the sky, </i>

685
00:42:37,119 --> 00:42:41,055
<i>and it was</i>
<i>a beautiful time. </i>
<i>[Phone Rings]</i>

686
00:42:41,123 --> 00:42:44,559
That'll be
Mr. Steve again.
<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>

687
00:42:48,964 --> 00:42:51,023
Hello?
Hello, Annie.

688
00:42:51,099 --> 00:42:54,262
- Oh, hello, Mr. Steve.
- Has she come in yet?

689
00:42:54,336 --> 00:42:56,463
I'm sorry.

690
00:42:56,538 --> 00:42:58,472
I see.

691
00:42:58,540 --> 00:43:00,599
Well, Merry Christmas,
Annie.

692
00:43:00,675 --> 00:43:02,802
Merry Christmas to you,
Mr. Steve.

693
00:43:02,878 --> 00:43:05,904
Mommy, isn't Steve
coming here tonight?

694
00:43:05,981 --> 00:43:08,916
I think you'd better
go to bed, both of you.

695
00:43:08,984 --> 00:43:11,350
But Annie was
telling us a story.

696
00:43:11,420 --> 00:43:14,355
Oh, all right,
Annie can finish it.
Where were we?

697
00:43:14,423 --> 00:43:16,687
- Jesus was almost borned.
- That's right.

698
00:43:16,758 --> 00:43:21,957
As soon as the holy infant
was born, three wise men saw
a beautiful star in the sky.

699
00:43:22,030 --> 00:43:24,965
The star
of Bethlehem...
Was Jesus white or black?

700
00:43:25,033 --> 00:43:27,968
It doesn't matter.
He's the way
you imagine him.

701
00:43:28,036 --> 00:43:30,698
But Annie said
he was a real man.

702
00:43:30,772 --> 00:43:32,706
He's not a pretend man.

703
00:43:32,774 --> 00:43:34,833
He was real.
He <i>is</i> real.

704
00:43:34,910 --> 00:43:36,844
Then what color was he?

705
00:43:36,912 --> 00:43:39,346
He was like me...
White.

706
00:43:43,514 --> 00:43:46,415
Now, the closet door
is over here.

707
00:43:46,483 --> 00:43:49,646
The clothes closet door
is over there.

708
00:43:49,720 --> 00:43:52,655
The door to your bedroom
is over here.

709
00:43:52,723 --> 00:43:56,159
And you trip over
the vacuum cleaner
over there.

710
00:43:58,061 --> 00:44:01,053
All right,
come on, let's have
your offstage line.

711
00:44:07,371 --> 00:44:08,998
<i>[Lora]</i>
<i>Is anybody home? </i>

712
00:44:09,072 --> 00:44:11,939
Marjorie?
Oh, Marjorie!

713
00:44:14,511 --> 00:44:17,446
Colonel, what are you
doing in there?

714
00:44:19,683 --> 00:44:22,618
Why, Mr. Obermeyer,
why aren't you in Duluth?

715
00:44:25,822 --> 00:44:27,756
Oh, Herbert, you too?

716
00:44:27,824 --> 00:44:30,486
<i>No! No, no, </i>
<i>Miss Meredith. </i>

717
00:44:30,561 --> 00:44:33,792
David, David.
She can do it, David.
I guarantee it.

718
00:44:33,864 --> 00:44:35,855
She's just
a little nervous.
Miss Meredith.

719
00:44:35,933 --> 00:44:38,026
Yes, sir?

720
00:44:38,101 --> 00:44:41,764
This scene is supposed to
be played for high comedy,
with delicate reactions,

721
00:44:41,838 --> 00:44:43,772
not loud,
goggle-eyed takes.

722
00:44:45,342 --> 00:44:47,333
I'm sorry, Mr. Edwards.

723
00:44:47,411 --> 00:44:51,438
But I'm an actress,
and a good one.

724
00:44:51,515 --> 00:44:55,178
But I couldn't play
this part for high comedy.
Nobody could.

725
00:44:55,252 --> 00:44:58,949
<i>Nobody. </i>
I think that's all,
Miss Meredith.

726
00:44:59,022 --> 00:45:01,957
<i>And if you'll forgive me</i>
<i>for saying it, </i>

727
00:45:02,025 --> 00:45:04,960
you're too good a writer
to have such a scene
in your play.

728
00:45:05,028 --> 00:45:07,861
Okay, sister,
this way out.

729
00:45:07,931 --> 00:45:12,425
I might as well confess...
She's not really my client.
Tell her to wait a minute.

730
00:45:16,974 --> 00:45:20,933
Lora!
Lora, wait a minute.

731
00:45:21,011 --> 00:45:23,946
I think we've still
got a chance.
No, I don't...

732
00:45:24,014 --> 00:45:25,948
Miss Meredith.

733
00:45:27,184 --> 00:45:30,415
It's been a long time
since anyone told me off.

734
00:45:30,487 --> 00:45:33,923
Tell me, what would you do
with that scene?

735
00:45:35,792 --> 00:45:38,727
I'd cut it out.
Drop it entirely.

736
00:45:39,796 --> 00:45:42,924
That's not a bad idea.
Let me think.

737
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:46,834
Yes, but the scene
has a couple of lines
that are important.

738
00:45:46,903 --> 00:45:48,837
Give them to Amy.

739
00:45:50,007 --> 00:45:52,066
Yes, it would work.

740
00:45:53,277 --> 00:45:55,541
Ha!
Think you could play Amy?

741
00:45:57,347 --> 00:46:00,009
Amy?

742
00:46:00,083 --> 00:46:03,519
Of course we'll have to
work very hard together.
I'd love it.

743
00:46:03,587 --> 00:46:06,021
So would I. Tom?
<i>Yes, Mr. Edwards. </i>

744
00:46:06,089 --> 00:46:10,116
Call off auditions
for the day. I'm busy.
[Whistles]

745
00:46:10,193 --> 00:46:13,128
You know, I always
believed in that girl.

746
00:46:14,765 --> 00:46:16,633
<i>[Applause]</i>

747
00:46:16,633 --> 00:46:17,861
<i>[Applause]</i>

748
00:46:26,676 --> 00:46:29,611
[Cheering,
Applause Continues]

749
00:46:35,318 --> 00:46:38,947
- Lora Meredith!
- Lora Meredith!

750
00:46:39,022 --> 00:46:43,322
<i>Lora Meredith! </i>
<i>Lora Meredith! </i>

751
00:46:43,393 --> 00:46:45,418
<i>[Applause Continues]</i>

752
00:46:56,706 --> 00:46:58,640
Thank you, David.

753
00:46:58,708 --> 00:47:02,405
They applauded me.
Did you hear them?
Why not? You were great!

754
00:47:02,479 --> 00:47:06,108
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Author! Author! </i>
Your turn, Mr. Edwards.

755
00:47:06,182 --> 00:47:08,616
Tom, may I borrow
a dime?
Sure.

756
00:47:08,685 --> 00:47:11,882
I'll pay you back.
Don't rush. You'll be
around a long time.

757
00:47:11,955 --> 00:47:13,889
I'll be right back.

758
00:47:18,728 --> 00:47:21,322
[Rings]

759
00:47:22,399 --> 00:47:24,333
Yes?

760
00:47:24,401 --> 00:47:26,335
Oh, Miss Lora!

761
00:47:27,537 --> 00:47:32,167
- And they liked me too.
- They did? Ohh!

762
00:47:32,242 --> 00:47:34,642
Now, isn't that wonderful?

763
00:47:34,711 --> 00:47:37,373
Do you want Susie?
Yes, please.

764
00:47:37,447 --> 00:47:39,381
[Whispers]
Congratulations,
mommy.

765
00:47:39,449 --> 00:47:43,283
Congratulations, Mommy.
Did you remember your lines?

766
00:47:43,353 --> 00:47:45,787
<i>[Applause Continues]</i>
Yes, I remembered
all my lines.

767
00:47:45,855 --> 00:47:48,790
Did they clap for you?
Yes, they did.

768
00:47:48,858 --> 00:47:52,555
I'll be home very soon.
I'll only stay
a little while.

769
00:47:52,629 --> 00:47:54,563
Then I'll come
right home.

770
00:47:54,631 --> 00:47:56,826
Here's a kiss,
mommy.
Ohh.

771
00:47:56,900 --> 00:47:59,334
And here's one
for you too. Mmm!

772
00:47:59,402 --> 00:48:03,338
Let's go. The paper's
will be out soon,
and the party's waiting.

773
00:48:04,407 --> 00:48:06,841
<i>[Party Guests Talking, </i>
<i>Laughing]</i>

774
00:48:06,910 --> 00:48:09,845
"This should be
a Pulitzer prize play
for David Edwards,

775
00:48:09,913 --> 00:48:12,780
"for tonight we saw
the ranking comedy
of the season,

776
00:48:12,849 --> 00:48:15,784
marvelously performed
by Geraldine Moore
and Preston Mitchell."

777
00:48:15,852 --> 00:48:18,412
[Talking, Laughing]
Listen
to the <i>Times. </i>

778
00:48:18,488 --> 00:48:20,922
Atkinson says,
"A new star was born.

779
00:48:20,990 --> 00:48:24,517
"Lora Meredith, an actress
who heretofore has been
hiding her light...

780
00:48:24,594 --> 00:48:26,528
"somewhere
in the hinterlands,

781
00:48:26,596 --> 00:48:30,032
gave a great performance
in a small part last night."
<i>[Guests Applauding]</i>

782
00:48:30,100 --> 00:48:32,534
Congratulations,
baby.
Thank you, Allen.

783
00:48:32,602 --> 00:48:34,536
<i>[Guests Talking]</i>
<i>[Woman] Congratulations. </i>
<i>That was really... </i>

784
00:48:34,604 --> 00:48:38,700
Lora, this is
a great night for us.
For <i>us? </i>

785
00:48:38,775 --> 00:48:40,902
Oh. Oh!

786
00:48:40,977 --> 00:48:44,572
Well, I for one can't keep
my beady eyes open anymore.

787
00:48:44,647 --> 00:48:47,081
I'm going home.
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Well, good night, David. </i>

788
00:48:47,150 --> 00:48:50,017
Good night,
all you lucky people.

789
00:48:50,086 --> 00:48:52,919
Good night.
Good night, dear.

790
00:48:52,989 --> 00:48:54,923
Good night.
Good night, David.

791
00:48:54,991 --> 00:48:56,925
Good night, Gerry.
Good night, David.

792
00:48:56,993 --> 00:48:58,927
See you tomorrow.
Good night,
David!

793
00:48:58,995 --> 00:49:00,929
Good night, all!
<i>[Guests]</i>
<i>Good night. </i>

794
00:49:00,997 --> 00:49:03,932
Congratulations again, baby.
We did it, all right.

795
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:07,436
I'll see you first thing
in the morning,
in my office.

796
00:49:09,672 --> 00:49:11,606
Agents.
[Chuckles]

797
00:49:11,674 --> 00:49:16,111
By morning it'll be all over
town that he wrote your part,
directed you personally...

798
00:49:16,179 --> 00:49:19,580
and was your lover
before you met me.

799
00:49:22,152 --> 00:49:24,416
Well, lady,
there's your new empire.

800
00:49:24,487 --> 00:49:28,787
<i>Not big, just stretches</i>
<i>from 42nd to 52nd street. </i>

801
00:49:28,858 --> 00:49:31,292
But it's
the heart of the world.

802
00:49:32,695 --> 00:49:35,755
You happy?
Oh, yes.

803
00:49:37,033 --> 00:49:38,967
Yes.

804
00:49:40,336 --> 00:49:44,295
I can't thank you...
I can't begin to
thank you for,

805
00:49:44,374 --> 00:49:46,308
for giving me the chance.

806
00:49:46,376 --> 00:49:48,310
No thanks.

807
00:49:48,378 --> 00:49:50,312
It's something
we did together.

808
00:49:53,049 --> 00:49:54,983
Yes.

809
00:49:56,719 --> 00:49:58,812
We'll have more evenings
like this.

810
00:49:58,888 --> 00:50:02,483
More plays.
I promise that.

811
00:50:03,226 --> 00:50:05,660
Please.

812
00:50:05,728 --> 00:50:07,992
And with you,
David.

813
00:50:08,064 --> 00:50:09,998
Always with you.

814
00:50:10,733 --> 00:50:12,667
You are good for me.

815
00:50:17,173 --> 00:50:19,107
You mean that?

816
00:50:19,175 --> 00:50:21,609
Well, you must be,
because l...

817
00:50:21,678 --> 00:50:24,613
I've never felt
this way before.

818
00:50:24,681 --> 00:50:27,616
Never so...
So complete...

819
00:50:27,684 --> 00:50:30,118
and so happy.

820
00:50:30,186 --> 00:50:34,122
I don't think
I could be happier
with anyone else either.

821
00:50:34,190 --> 00:50:36,624
I'm in love
with you, Lora.

822
00:50:36,693 --> 00:50:40,686
Though I must hasten to add,
I always fall in love
with my leading ladies.

823
00:50:40,763 --> 00:50:43,129
Maybe that's all it is.

824
00:50:43,199 --> 00:50:45,394
But I don't care,

825
00:50:45,468 --> 00:50:48,164
because
I'm loving you now.

826
00:50:48,238 --> 00:50:50,832
You and tonight.

827
00:50:50,907 --> 00:50:52,841
Thank you.

828
00:52:02,712 --> 00:52:04,646
[Knock On Door]

829
00:52:07,216 --> 00:52:09,150
Marvelous performance,
darling.

830
00:52:09,218 --> 00:52:12,085
Just as fresh as it was
seven months ago.
Hmm.

831
00:52:12,155 --> 00:52:14,851
Now hurry up
and get ready.
David.

832
00:52:14,924 --> 00:52:18,860
Can't I beg off tonight?
I am so...
Beg off?
Impossible, darling.

833
00:52:18,928 --> 00:52:21,863
Some nice, untouched money
out there from Cincinnati.

834
00:52:21,931 --> 00:52:25,367
Hardware. They want to
meet you to invest in your
success and my next play.

835
00:52:25,435 --> 00:52:28,871
She oughta go to bed now.
Annie, you're much too pretty
to be a watchdog.

836
00:52:28,938 --> 00:52:31,372
And I can bite
sometimes.
Five minutes.

837
00:52:31,441 --> 00:52:34,933
But darling...
While I keep Cincinnati
and the money happy.

838
00:52:35,011 --> 00:52:37,445
Doesn't he ever stop?

839
00:52:37,513 --> 00:52:39,447
He can't, Annie.

840
00:52:39,515 --> 00:52:43,952
If he did
he'd be sure to find out
how sad he really is.

841
00:52:45,521 --> 00:52:47,455
And I know that feeling.

842
00:52:48,858 --> 00:52:50,792
Funny, isn't it?

843
00:52:50,860 --> 00:52:55,559
After all this time,
the struggling and heartache,

844
00:52:55,632 --> 00:52:58,066
and you make it.

845
00:52:58,134 --> 00:53:02,070
Then you find out
it doesn't seem worth it.

846
00:53:02,138 --> 00:53:04,072
Something is missing.

847
00:53:05,508 --> 00:53:07,942
Now David
wants to marry me.

848
00:53:08,011 --> 00:53:10,741
I don't know.
Do you love him?

849
00:53:12,482 --> 00:53:14,746
No.

850
00:53:14,817 --> 00:53:17,911
But he's good for me
in many ways.

851
00:53:17,987 --> 00:53:21,423
At least I'm trying to
make myself think he is.

852
00:53:21,491 --> 00:53:24,927
And of course it...
It would be better
for Susie.

853
00:53:24,994 --> 00:53:27,428
This ain't no time
to make decisions.

854
00:53:27,497 --> 00:53:30,432
You're tired, and you don't
know what you want.

855
00:53:33,002 --> 00:53:35,937
Maybe I don't want
so much anymore.

856
00:53:36,005 --> 00:53:39,941
But what would you do
if you gave it all up?

857
00:53:40,009 --> 00:53:43,445
Well, I could spend
more time with Susie.

858
00:53:43,513 --> 00:53:46,448
And you could stay home
with Sarah Jane.

859
00:53:47,517 --> 00:53:49,451
Do you know,

860
00:53:49,519 --> 00:53:52,955
I haven't been up to see
my baby at school in weeks.

861
00:53:53,022 --> 00:53:54,956
Susie knows you love her.

862
00:53:55,024 --> 00:53:58,960
And you need show business
as much as it needs you.

863
00:54:00,430 --> 00:54:04,764
Oh, Annie, what would
I do without you?
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

864
00:54:06,469 --> 00:54:08,664
Well. Beautiful.

865
00:54:08,738 --> 00:54:10,603
Do you really
like it?

866
00:54:10,673 --> 00:54:13,733
You're more beautiful
than I could ever
possibly remember.

867
00:54:13,810 --> 00:54:15,744
And we're late.

868
00:54:15,812 --> 00:54:19,873
Good night, Annie.
You see she gets home
at a decent hour.

869
00:54:29,658 --> 00:54:32,684
Annie, I think
we'll try these,
uh, over here.

870
00:54:32,761 --> 00:54:36,197
Miss Lora, we been
spending an awful lot
of money up here.

871
00:54:36,265 --> 00:54:41,760
Do you think we can really
afford to have this place?
We can't afford not to.

872
00:54:41,837 --> 00:54:43,771
<i>Ma'am? Ma'am? </i>
Oh, um...

873
00:54:43,839 --> 00:54:48,276
Would you put it
over there, please?
In front of the window.

874
00:54:53,515 --> 00:54:55,449
Oh, that's fine.

875
00:54:55,517 --> 00:54:58,145
Would you
sign this, ma'am?
Mm-hmm.

876
00:55:00,723 --> 00:55:02,657
Thank you very much.

877
00:55:02,725 --> 00:55:04,659
Come on, let's go, Joe.

878
00:55:07,363 --> 00:55:11,231
Did you see the bills
from Susie's new school?
Mm-hmm.

879
00:55:11,300 --> 00:55:13,234
And it doesn't matter.
But Miss Lora...

880
00:55:13,302 --> 00:55:17,739
No matter what it costs,
Susie's going to have
everything that I missed.

881
00:55:17,806 --> 00:55:21,242
From her letters
she misses you more than
she'd ever miss Latin.

882
00:55:21,310 --> 00:55:23,744
She just wrote
and told me...
Annie.

883
00:55:23,812 --> 00:55:27,248
You still haven't told me what
the doctor said about those
spells you've been getting.

884
00:55:27,316 --> 00:55:31,252
What do doctors always say
when they can't find nothin'
wrong? "Take it easy."

885
00:55:31,320 --> 00:55:33,754
Well, do.
And I mean it.
Oh, Miss Lora...

886
00:55:33,822 --> 00:55:36,757
You can have anyone
you want in here
to help you.

887
00:55:36,825 --> 00:55:40,090
Be more work gettin' 'em
out of my way.
<i>[Doorbell Rings]</i>

888
00:55:40,162 --> 00:55:42,096
<i>I'll get it. </i>

889
00:55:44,667 --> 00:55:47,101
Hello, Mr. Edwards.
Hello, Sarah Jane.

890
00:55:47,169 --> 00:55:49,103
How are you?
Fine, thanks.

891
00:55:49,171 --> 00:55:52,436
I'm going to The Village.
I'll be back by 3:00.

892
00:55:52,508 --> 00:55:55,944
Annie,
that daughter of yours
gets prettier every day.

893
00:55:56,011 --> 00:55:57,945
And so
sophisticated.

894
00:55:58,013 --> 00:56:00,948
Darling.
Hello, dear.

895
00:56:01,016 --> 00:56:03,450
Oh. Nice.
Yes. It's new.

896
00:56:03,519 --> 00:56:05,453
Didn't you get
my messages yesterday?

897
00:56:05,521 --> 00:56:07,955
Or have you given up
telephones?

898
00:56:08,023 --> 00:56:13,461
Uh, well, we've been so busy
getting the house in order.
<i><music>[Hi-Fi: Orchestra]</i>

899
00:56:13,529 --> 00:56:15,463
Come sit down.

900
00:56:17,633 --> 00:56:20,568
Would you like a drink?
A long one. It's quite
a trek from Manhattan.

901
00:56:20,636 --> 00:56:22,570
Your usual?
Uh-huh.

902
00:56:22,638 --> 00:56:25,072
I'll get it.
All right,
enough chitchat.

903
00:56:25,140 --> 00:56:27,233
Have you read
my new play?

904
00:56:27,309 --> 00:56:30,642
Great, isn't it?
[Sighs]
Yes, it's very good.

905
00:56:30,713 --> 00:56:32,704
But David...

906
00:56:33,982 --> 00:56:36,917
Darling, I don't think
I should do another comedy.

907
00:56:36,985 --> 00:56:38,919
No, no, wait a minute.

908
00:56:38,987 --> 00:56:43,924
I've decided to do
the new Stewart play.
That? What part?

909
00:56:43,992 --> 00:56:47,928
Not the dull social worker
with the high dreams
and low heels.

910
00:56:47,996 --> 00:56:50,191
Yes.
It's drama.
No clothes, no sex.

911
00:56:50,265 --> 00:56:52,392
No fun!
I know.

912
00:56:52,468 --> 00:56:55,403
But it's a great chance for...
For good acting.

913
00:56:55,471 --> 00:56:58,406
<i>And that colored angle</i>
<i>in it, it's absolutely</i>
<i>controversial. </i>

914
00:56:58,474 --> 00:57:00,999
<i>- What do you know</i>
<i>about controversy? </i>
- Nothing.

915
00:57:01,076 --> 00:57:03,010
And I don't want to know.

916
00:57:03,078 --> 00:57:07,014
I only know it's a good script,
and they're not easy to find.

917
00:57:07,082 --> 00:57:11,951
Besides, l, I feel I need
something different,
a new experience.

918
00:57:12,020 --> 00:57:15,456
<i>All right, </i>
<i>if you want a flop, </i>
<i>have it on your own time. </i>

919
00:57:15,524 --> 00:57:18,960
I wrote my play for you.
I tailored it
to your every mood.

920
00:57:19,027 --> 00:57:21,962
I never wrote
better laughs
in my life!

921
00:57:22,030 --> 00:57:24,965
And you tell me
you want controversy.
Hmph!

922
00:57:25,033 --> 00:57:28,969
It may sound ungrateful,
after all you've done for me.

923
00:57:29,037 --> 00:57:30,971
You're right.
It is ungrateful.

924
00:57:31,039 --> 00:57:32,973
But then I never
expected gratitude.

925
00:57:33,041 --> 00:57:36,340
Personally,
I couldn't stand it.

926
00:57:36,411 --> 00:57:38,845
May I have
my property back?

927
00:57:38,914 --> 00:57:41,144
Of course.

928
00:57:45,988 --> 00:57:47,922
Good luck, David.

929
00:57:47,990 --> 00:57:50,424
I know
it will be a hit.

930
00:57:50,492 --> 00:57:53,427
It won't without you.

931
00:57:53,495 --> 00:57:56,089
It'll never be done.

932
00:57:56,165 --> 00:58:00,101
Under the circumstances
I think it's best
if I destroy this.

933
00:58:00,169 --> 00:58:03,229
<i>What? </i>
<i>[Annie]</i>
<i>But Mr. Edwards... </i>

934
00:58:03,305 --> 00:58:07,241
There goes my pride,
up in ashes.

935
00:58:07,309 --> 00:58:09,607
Well, good-bye.

936
00:58:09,678 --> 00:58:11,543
What...

937
00:58:11,613 --> 00:58:14,047
Just a theatrical
gesture.

938
00:58:14,116 --> 00:58:17,051
He never makes less
than six copies.

939
00:58:17,119 --> 00:58:18,653
<i>[Applause]</i>

940
00:58:18,653 --> 00:58:20,553
<i>[Applause]</i>

941
00:58:32,300 --> 00:58:34,234
Wasn't she great?

942
00:58:34,302 --> 00:58:37,237
You're going to join us,
aren't you?
No.

943
00:58:37,305 --> 00:58:40,536
Just wish her all the luck
in the world for me.

944
00:58:40,609 --> 00:58:42,543
Tell her
I was wrong.

945
00:58:45,280 --> 00:58:48,716
Oh, Annie,
wasn't Mother
just wonderful?

946
00:58:48,783 --> 00:58:53,584
Susie! Susie, wait!
I've got to hurry.
Mama's bringing them all home.

947
00:58:53,655 --> 00:58:55,782
Sarah Jane!

948
00:59:00,862 --> 00:59:02,796
Oh, yes!
Thank you.

949
00:59:02,864 --> 00:59:05,799
Oh, that's very sweet.
Darling,
you were wonderful.

950
00:59:05,867 --> 00:59:09,564
How sweet.
Wasn't it... Steve!
[Guests Talking]

951
00:59:09,638 --> 00:59:13,369
Hello, Lora.
And congratulations.

952
00:59:13,441 --> 00:59:15,966
Oh, Steve,
I can't believe it.

953
00:59:16,044 --> 00:59:19,980
Oh, Lora, I'd... I'd like you
to know Louise Morton.
How do you do?

954
00:59:20,048 --> 00:59:22,983
How do you do,
Miss Meredith?
I loved your performance.

955
00:59:23,051 --> 00:59:24,985
Thank you very much.

956
00:59:25,053 --> 00:59:27,044
Um, Steve Archer,
everybody.

957
00:59:27,122 --> 00:59:29,556
How do you do?
<i>[Guests Together]</i>
<i>How do you do? </i>

958
00:59:29,624 --> 00:59:32,058
A very old
and dear friend.

959
00:59:32,127 --> 00:59:34,391
Oh, and, uh,
Miss Morton.

960
00:59:34,462 --> 00:59:36,896
Hi. Hello.
<i>[Guest]</i>
<i>Nice meeting you. </i>

961
00:59:36,965 --> 00:59:39,058
Oh, Steve,
it's been so long.

962
00:59:39,134 --> 00:59:43,070
Ten years.
Oh, and you haven't
changed a bit.

963
00:59:43,138 --> 00:59:46,073
How are Annie
and the kids?
Oh, Annie's fine.

964
00:59:46,141 --> 00:59:50,077
You'd never know
the children, they're
so grown-up and lovely.

965
00:59:50,145 --> 00:59:54,081
Uh, look, we're
all going to my house
to wait for the reviews.

966
00:59:54,149 --> 00:59:57,585
- Why don't you join us?
- Well, let's get going.

967
00:59:57,652 --> 01:00:01,088
<i>[Woman] You mind us</i>
<i>riding with you folks? </i>
<i>Fine. We have plenty of room. </i>

968
01:00:01,156 --> 01:00:04,091
<i>That'd be nice. </i>
<i>All right. </i>

969
01:00:10,165 --> 01:00:13,100
Mmm. I'm glad
the opening's over.

970
01:00:13,168 --> 01:00:17,104
Now I hope Mother will
have some time for me
before my graduation.

971
01:00:17,172 --> 01:00:21,108
I have a lot of subjects
I wanna discuss with her.
I don't want to forget any.

972
01:00:21,176 --> 01:00:24,111
Annie, do you wanna
hear them?
Sure, honey.

973
01:00:24,179 --> 01:00:27,910
The most important
is Jane Beeler's party.
There are gonna be boys.

974
01:00:27,983 --> 01:00:31,419
And under that
I have an "A" and a "B"
I wanna discuss with Mother.

975
01:00:31,486 --> 01:00:35,422
A... How do I make
a boy like me, and B...
Should I let him kiss me.

976
01:00:35,490 --> 01:00:38,425
Isn't that subject
comin' up a little soon?

977
01:00:38,493 --> 01:00:41,656
The girls in school
discuss it all the time.
<i>[Doorbell Rings]</i>

978
01:00:41,730 --> 01:00:43,664
[Guests Chattering]

979
01:00:43,732 --> 01:00:46,701
My goodness!
They're here already!

980
01:00:48,970 --> 01:00:52,565
Honey, will you run upstairs
and get Sarah Jane?
All right.

981
01:00:56,311 --> 01:00:58,404
All right, ma'am?
It's wonderful.

982
01:00:58,480 --> 01:01:00,414
Thank you.
<i><music>[Piano]</i>

983
01:01:01,750 --> 01:01:05,186
Annie, are you ready
for a surprise?

984
01:01:06,788 --> 01:01:08,722
Wait till you see
who's here.

985
01:01:10,325 --> 01:01:12,259
Hello, Annie.

986
01:01:12,327 --> 01:01:14,261
Why, Mr. Steve!

987
01:01:14,329 --> 01:01:17,389
Oh, my goodness!
I'll get you
a drink.

988
01:01:17,465 --> 01:01:19,399
You certainly
look fine!

989
01:01:19,467 --> 01:01:21,901
You too, Annie.
How's everything been?

990
01:01:21,970 --> 01:01:24,404
Each day
I count my blessings.

991
01:01:24,472 --> 01:01:27,908
You call doing this
at 1:00 in the morning
a blessing?
Yes, sir.

992
01:01:27,976 --> 01:01:31,412
I can remember when plenty
of ham and eggs was more
than a blessing.

993
01:01:31,479 --> 01:01:33,413
It was a miracle.

994
01:01:33,481 --> 01:01:35,915
Here you are.
Scotch and water.
I remembered.

995
01:01:35,984 --> 01:01:38,919
Thanks, but I'd better
get back to Louise.

996
01:01:38,987 --> 01:01:40,921
She won't even
know you're there.

997
01:01:40,989 --> 01:01:43,423
She's being mesmerized
by Allen Loomis.

998
01:01:43,491 --> 01:01:46,927
Oh, Steve, it's good
to have you here.
I mean it.

999
01:01:46,995 --> 01:01:50,431
Now that we
finally have you back,
we will not let you go.

1000
01:01:50,498 --> 01:01:53,934
No, sir, you're
gonna stay with us.
Listen.

1001
01:01:54,002 --> 01:01:57,631
I have this Sunday off,
the first Sunday I've had
in weeks.

1002
01:01:57,705 --> 01:02:01,505
We're going to drive into
the country for a picnic,
Susie, Sarah Jane and Annie.

1003
01:02:01,576 --> 01:02:04,409
How does that sound?
Wonderful.

1004
01:02:04,479 --> 01:02:07,505
<i>Steve! </i>
<i>I heard your voice! </i>

1005
01:02:07,582 --> 01:02:09,516
Ohh!
[Laughing]

1006
01:02:09,584 --> 01:02:13,384
This can't be Susie.
So pretty, and not
little anymore.

1007
01:02:13,455 --> 01:02:16,390
Little?
Why, I'm graduating
in two weeks!

1008
01:02:16,458 --> 01:02:19,518
You'll come, won't you?
I wouldn't miss it
for the world.

1009
01:02:19,594 --> 01:02:21,528
Sarah Jane,
look who's here.

1010
01:02:23,198 --> 01:02:25,894
Sarah Jane?
Hello, Steve.

1011
01:02:26,968 --> 01:02:30,404
It can't be.
Why, you were all legs.

1012
01:02:30,472 --> 01:02:33,635
I still have them.
Yes, but they
came up to here.

1013
01:02:33,708 --> 01:02:35,642
[Laughs]

1014
01:02:35,710 --> 01:02:39,111
Steve, don't ever
go away from us again.
Will you promise?

1015
01:02:39,180 --> 01:02:42,274
<i>Well, are we holding</i>
<i>the party in here? </i>
<i>Hi, Annie, Sarah Jane. </i>

1016
01:02:42,350 --> 01:02:44,284
No, Allen,
we're coming right out.

1017
01:02:44,352 --> 01:02:46,786
<i><music>[Continues]</i>
<i>[Guests Chattering]</i>

1018
01:02:49,224 --> 01:02:52,489
What a surprise
to see you.
Wonderful
to see you again.

1019
01:02:54,529 --> 01:02:58,465
You have an open invitation
to come here any time you can
get away from Madison avenue.

1020
01:02:58,533 --> 01:03:01,502
Oh, yes, not just anytime,
but all the time.
Come on.

1021
01:03:01,569 --> 01:03:04,197
Even though it is
a long drive.

1022
01:03:04,272 --> 01:03:09,209
You forget I used to walk up
three flights of stairs to
see you in the old days.

1023
01:03:09,277 --> 01:03:12,144
Oh, Mama, look!
A falling star!

1024
01:03:12,213 --> 01:03:14,647
[Guests Murmuring
Excitedly]

1025
01:03:17,318 --> 01:03:19,809
The food's on.

1026
01:03:19,888 --> 01:03:22,015
Excuse me.

1027
01:03:27,595 --> 01:03:30,189
Did you wish on it?
Mm-hmm.

1028
01:03:31,933 --> 01:03:35,869
I wish it could always
be like tonight.

1029
01:03:35,937 --> 01:03:38,872
All of us together.
Don't you?

1030
01:03:41,109 --> 01:03:43,043
Yes, my darling.

1031
01:03:44,379 --> 01:03:47,815
And I'm going to
do something about it.

1032
01:03:47,882 --> 01:03:52,046
I will not do another play
for a long, long time.

1033
01:03:52,120 --> 01:03:55,419
Ohh, Mama!
Come in.

1034
01:04:09,470 --> 01:04:11,335
We're goin' now,
honey.

1035
01:04:11,406 --> 01:04:15,342
If that headache ain't gone
in an hour's time,
you take another aspirin.

1036
01:04:15,410 --> 01:04:18,504
You hear?
Yes, Mama.
Have a good time.

1037
01:04:18,580 --> 01:04:21,014
Mama.
Yes, baby?

1038
01:04:21,082 --> 01:04:25,178
Tell 'em I'm... I'm sorry
I had to miss the picnic.

1039
01:04:25,253 --> 01:04:27,187
Okay. Okay.

1040
01:04:46,274 --> 01:04:49,710
But by the time I find Steve
the fire'll be just perfect.

1041
01:04:49,777 --> 01:04:52,746
You let them alone.
Maybe they got things
to talk about.

1042
01:04:52,814 --> 01:04:54,748
This is
a fine picnic.

1043
01:04:54,816 --> 01:04:59,753
Sarah Jane announces
she's getting the flu.
Mom and Steve just go off.

1044
01:04:59,821 --> 01:05:04,258
Oh, well, if this is the way
it's gonna be, I might as
well get on with my list.

1045
01:05:04,325 --> 01:05:09,262
I can cross off pink sweater
for Elizabeth and yellow
sweater for Sarah Jane.

1046
01:05:09,330 --> 01:05:11,264
Then we skip ahead
to algebra.

1047
01:05:11,332 --> 01:05:15,268
Do you think another year of
that stuff is a good idea?
I sure do.

1048
01:05:15,336 --> 01:05:18,772
It's gonna come in
mighty handy with prices
always goin' up.

1049
01:05:18,840 --> 01:05:21,274
Which brings us
back to boys.

1050
01:05:21,342 --> 01:05:24,277
What do you think
about kissing, Annie?
[Laughs]

1051
01:05:24,345 --> 01:05:28,042
Well, there's kissin'
and <i>kissin'. </i>

1052
01:05:28,116 --> 01:05:31,051
I still take pictures
every chance I get.

1053
01:05:31,119 --> 01:05:33,553
Still trying
to get them exhibited.
Stop hedging.

1054
01:05:33,621 --> 01:05:35,555
What is your job,
really?

1055
01:05:35,623 --> 01:05:38,558
I'm Vice President
in Charge of Advertising
for P.C. Beer.

1056
01:05:38,626 --> 01:05:41,561
Don't tell anybody.
Why not?
I think it's wonderful.

1057
01:05:41,629 --> 01:05:46,328
'Cause I'm quitting
just as soon as I can
wind things up.
But why?

1058
01:05:46,401 --> 01:05:49,837
You ever get the feeling
that you're tired of
what you're doing,

1059
01:05:49,904 --> 01:05:52,338
that it isn't all
you really wanted?

1060
01:05:52,407 --> 01:05:56,343
Did you ever get the urge
not to do what you don't
want to do?

1061
01:05:56,411 --> 01:06:00,347
To let yourself go
and follow the wind
or a star,

1062
01:06:00,415 --> 01:06:02,849
maybe even
a dusty old rainbow?

1063
01:06:02,917 --> 01:06:04,851
Yes.

1064
01:06:04,919 --> 01:06:06,853
Well, that's why
I'm going.

1065
01:06:06,921 --> 01:06:08,855
Where to?

1066
01:06:08,923 --> 01:06:12,290
I don't know.
Around the world,
I guess, for a start.

1067
01:06:12,360 --> 01:06:14,294
You going alone?

1068
01:06:14,362 --> 01:06:18,924
I'm afraid so, l...
I went through my entire
little black book.

1069
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:21,935
Well, you shouldn't have
skipped my name.

1070
01:06:23,037 --> 01:06:26,871
l... I don't know why
I said that, Steve,

1071
01:06:26,941 --> 01:06:30,377
except that
I haven't been this happy
with anyone for years.

1072
01:06:30,445 --> 01:06:35,007
You know I still have you
in my blood, don't you?
Oh, Steve, do you really?

1073
01:06:36,584 --> 01:06:39,018
I never got over you,
Lora.

1074
01:06:39,087 --> 01:06:42,181
No matter how hard I tried,
I couldn't.

1075
01:06:45,093 --> 01:06:48,529
There's a kind of kissin'
that's not careless
and doesn't lead to harm,

1076
01:06:48,596 --> 01:06:51,531
when the two people kissin'
are nice and right.

1077
01:06:51,599 --> 01:06:53,533
Kissin' is part of
fallin' in love.

1078
01:06:53,601 --> 01:06:56,035
The Lord
wants his children
to fall in love,

1079
01:06:56,104 --> 01:06:58,538
when they're old enough
and got sense enough.

1080
01:06:58,606 --> 01:07:01,541
Then kissin' is like
yeast is to bread...

1081
01:07:01,609 --> 01:07:05,204
Pardon me, Annie,
but I'm starving.
Can't I please find Steve?

1082
01:07:05,279 --> 01:07:07,213
Don't think
you'll have to.

1083
01:07:07,281 --> 01:07:11,149
Steve! It's time
to cook the steaks!
Even Annie says so!

1084
01:07:11,219 --> 01:07:13,153
[Lora, Susie Giggling]

1085
01:07:13,221 --> 01:07:16,156
Telling them
will be wonderful,
but Loomis, ohh.

1086
01:07:16,224 --> 01:07:20,160
Why tell him at all?
He has a lot of commitments
he'll have to get me out of.

1087
01:07:20,228 --> 01:07:23,493
<i>[Annie]</i>
<i>Susie, will you go see</i>
<i>how Sarah Jane is? </i>

1088
01:07:23,564 --> 01:07:26,328
Tell her
I'll be right up.
Okay.

1089
01:07:27,635 --> 01:07:31,162
Let me help you
with that.
Thank you, honey.

1090
01:07:34,242 --> 01:07:36,767
Hello, Allen?
l...

1091
01:07:37,845 --> 01:07:39,779
You've been trying
to call me?

1092
01:07:39,847 --> 01:07:42,281
I'm sorry.
We've been out all day.

1093
01:07:42,350 --> 01:07:44,841
<i>When? </i>

1094
01:07:44,919 --> 01:07:49,356
Oh. Well, that sounds
simply marvelous, but...

1095
01:07:49,424 --> 01:07:52,359
Uh, no, not for dinner.
I'm having guests.

1096
01:07:53,694 --> 01:07:56,629
Why don't you bring him
for cocktails.

1097
01:07:56,697 --> 01:07:59,188
Yes. All right.

1098
01:08:00,935 --> 01:08:04,132
Steve!
Amerigo Felluci!

1099
01:08:04,205 --> 01:08:06,673
The Italian
movie director.
<i>Yes. </i>

1100
01:08:06,741 --> 01:08:11,201
Oh, he wants me
for the part of Rena
in <i>No More Laughter. </i>

1101
01:08:11,279 --> 01:08:15,613
<i>His agent is in New York</i>
<i>now to talk to me about it. </i>
I see.

1102
01:08:15,683 --> 01:08:19,119
- That means you'd
have to go to Italy.
- Mmm. Of course.

1103
01:08:20,354 --> 01:08:22,288
Oh.

1104
01:08:23,724 --> 01:08:27,490
Well, I'll have to
give a two-week notice
to the play.

1105
01:08:27,562 --> 01:08:29,826
Yes.

1106
01:08:29,897 --> 01:08:32,058
Well,
don't be so calm.

1107
01:08:32,133 --> 01:08:34,067
They want me
for Rena!

1108
01:08:34,135 --> 01:08:38,572
Well, who is she?
Only the best part
since Scarlett O'Hara.

1109
01:08:42,777 --> 01:08:45,678
Sarah Jane?

1110
01:09:06,033 --> 01:09:08,968
Sarah Jane!
Where have you been?

1111
01:09:09,036 --> 01:09:12,972
I've been looking all over
for you! You're supposed
to be in bed...
Shh!

1112
01:09:20,114 --> 01:09:22,048
Uh...

1113
01:09:22,116 --> 01:09:24,050
Sit down.

1114
01:09:25,953 --> 01:09:27,887
Cross your heart.

1115
01:09:29,423 --> 01:09:32,358
You won't tell my mama?
No, I won't
tell Annie.

1116
01:09:32,426 --> 01:09:34,860
W-Well, what is it?

1117
01:09:35,796 --> 01:09:37,730
I've been out.

1118
01:09:38,833 --> 01:09:41,199
With my boyfriend.

1119
01:09:41,268 --> 01:09:45,204
Boyfriend?
I didn't know
you had a boyfriend!

1120
01:09:45,272 --> 01:09:48,400
- Where's he from?
- The Village.

1121
01:09:48,476 --> 01:09:51,912
Oh. Did you meet him
in school?
<i>School? </i>

1122
01:09:52,980 --> 01:09:54,914
No.

1123
01:09:54,982 --> 01:09:57,917
There's an ice cream
parlor in The Village
with a jukebox.

1124
01:09:57,985 --> 01:10:01,148
Yeah?
And he used to
stand outside,

1125
01:10:01,222 --> 01:10:05,488
and every time I'd walk by,
he'd whistle!
No kidding!

1126
01:10:05,559 --> 01:10:09,495
But first I pretended he
wasn't on earth.
Yeah?
[Giggles]

1127
01:10:09,563 --> 01:10:12,498
But finally I had to laugh,
and he followed me.
<music> [Orchestra]

1128
01:10:12,566 --> 01:10:15,000
And we started to talk.

1129
01:10:15,069 --> 01:10:18,402
He's cute.
<i>Really</i> cute.
[Sighs]

1130
01:10:18,472 --> 01:10:20,406
Is he a colored boy?

1131
01:10:20,474 --> 01:10:23,739
Why did you ask that?
Well, I don't know.

1132
01:10:23,811 --> 01:10:26,746
It just slipped out.
It was the first thing
you thought of.

1133
01:10:26,814 --> 01:10:29,749
I told you,
it just slipped out!
Well, he's white.

1134
01:10:29,817 --> 01:10:34,754
And if he ever finds out
about me, I'll kill myself.
But why?

1135
01:10:34,822 --> 01:10:38,553
Because I'm white too.
And if I have to be colored,
then I want to die.

1136
01:10:38,626 --> 01:10:41,595
What are you saying?
I wanna have
a chance in life.

1137
01:10:41,662 --> 01:10:45,257
I don't wanna have to
come through back doors,
feel lower than other people,

1138
01:10:45,332 --> 01:10:48,267
or apologize
for my mother's color.
Don't say that!

1139
01:10:48,335 --> 01:10:51,498
She can't help her color,
but I can.

1140
01:10:51,572 --> 01:10:53,506
And I will.

1141
01:10:53,574 --> 01:10:56,008
But we've always
talked things over.

1142
01:10:56,076 --> 01:10:58,704
You never told me
this before.

1143
01:10:58,779 --> 01:11:00,713
<music> [Continues]

1144
01:11:02,783 --> 01:11:05,718
Because I've never had
a boyfriend before.

1145
01:11:07,288 --> 01:11:10,155
Because he wants to
marry me someday.

1146
01:11:11,659 --> 01:11:14,594
A white boy.
Me.

1147
01:11:14,662 --> 01:11:19,395
But how do you think
he'd feel, or his folks,
with a black in-law?

1148
01:11:19,466 --> 01:11:23,402
What do you think people
would say where we lived
if they knew my mother...

1149
01:11:23,470 --> 01:11:27,668
They'd spit at me.
And my children.

1150
01:11:27,741 --> 01:11:30,676
Sarah Jane,
you know that's not true!
It is.

1151
01:11:30,744 --> 01:11:33,178
That's why
he mustn't know her.

1152
01:11:33,247 --> 01:11:35,681
I don't want anybody
to know her.

1153
01:11:35,749 --> 01:11:39,685
What if he comes here?
He doesn't even know
where I live.

1154
01:11:39,753 --> 01:11:43,189
I pretend I'm a...
I'm a rich girl
with strict parents.

1155
01:11:43,257 --> 01:11:45,885
Well, he's bound
to find out...
How?

1156
01:11:47,194 --> 01:11:50,186
I'm going to be everything
he thinks I am.

1157
01:11:50,264 --> 01:11:53,427
I look it, and that's
all that matters.

1158
01:11:53,500 --> 01:11:56,936
And you're not to say
anything either.
I won't. You know I won't.

1159
01:11:57,004 --> 01:11:58,938
I never did, but...

1160
01:11:59,006 --> 01:12:02,601
Sarah Jane,
if Mama ever found out
she'd never stand for it.

1161
01:12:02,676 --> 01:12:04,610
I don't care.

1162
01:12:06,146 --> 01:12:08,580
Your mother
doesn't own me.

1163
01:12:10,618 --> 01:12:13,917
I won't be seeing you
before you leave,
so good luck in Italy.

1164
01:12:13,988 --> 01:12:15,922
You make that sound
like good-bye.

1165
01:12:15,990 --> 01:12:18,925
Why couldn't
we meet in Italy?
What for?

1166
01:12:18,993 --> 01:12:22,258
You'll have a film.
You won't need me.

1167
01:12:22,329 --> 01:12:24,263
But Steve, wait.

1168
01:12:24,331 --> 01:12:28,563
You tell Susie I'll
be at her graduation.
Good-bye, Lora.

1169
01:12:34,108 --> 01:12:36,042
<i>[Car Door Opens]</i>

1170
01:12:47,214 --> 01:12:49,375
Oh, Sarah Jane.
Yes, Miss Lora?

1171
01:12:49,450 --> 01:12:52,385
I'm having
some people come
for a business meeting.

1172
01:12:52,453 --> 01:12:56,389
Later the dinner guests
will arrive. Could you
help your mother a bit?

1173
01:12:56,457 --> 01:12:59,324
Miss Lora,
l... l-I'd like to,
but I have a...

1174
01:12:59,393 --> 01:13:02,760
A date?
Is it the Hawkins boy?

1175
01:13:02,830 --> 01:13:04,764
Hawkins?

1176
01:13:04,832 --> 01:13:08,563
<i>Well, the Miller's chauffeur</i>
<i>down the road. </i>
Why do you say that?

1177
01:13:08,636 --> 01:13:12,163
I met him at the station
the other day
and he asked about you.

1178
01:13:12,239 --> 01:13:15,174
No.
It's with someone else.

1179
01:13:15,242 --> 01:13:17,176
Oh.

1180
01:13:17,244 --> 01:13:20,680
All right, you run along.
I'll try to manage here.
<i>[Doorbell Rings]</i>

1181
01:13:20,748 --> 01:13:22,682
Oh, there they are.

1182
01:13:33,627 --> 01:13:37,654
Look, honey, why don't you
go over to the party
at the church?

1183
01:13:37,731 --> 01:13:39,665
They bore me.

1184
01:13:39,733 --> 01:13:44,670
You're makin' a big mistake.
You're young. You shouldn't
be sittin' around.

1185
01:13:44,738 --> 01:13:46,672
Miss Lora
feels the same way.

1186
01:13:46,740 --> 01:13:51,677
She'll lend you
her car.
Oh, she will?
How nice of her.

1187
01:13:51,745 --> 01:13:54,680
I'd be happy knowin'
you're meetin'
nice young folks.

1188
01:13:54,748 --> 01:13:57,683
Busboys, cooks,
chauffeurs!

1189
01:13:57,751 --> 01:14:00,686
Hmph.
Like Hawkins.

1190
01:14:00,754 --> 01:14:04,190
No, thank you.
I've seen your
"nice young folks."

1191
01:14:05,326 --> 01:14:08,261
I don't wanna fight
with you, honey.

1192
01:14:08,329 --> 01:14:10,194
Not tonight.

1193
01:14:10,264 --> 01:14:12,198
I don't feel too good.

1194
01:14:12,266 --> 01:14:14,700
While I get started
on the anchovies,

1195
01:14:14,768 --> 01:14:17,703
will you take this tray
into Miss Lora
and her friends?

1196
01:14:17,771 --> 01:14:19,705
Why, certainly.

1197
01:14:19,773 --> 01:14:22,708
Anything at all
for Miss Lora
and her friends.

1198
01:14:25,479 --> 01:14:28,915
But signor Romano, why should
she need rehearsals?
<i>Ma scusa, signor. </i>

1199
01:14:28,983 --> 01:14:30,917
You know her work.

1200
01:14:30,985 --> 01:14:33,613
Felluci always insists
on two weeks' rehearsal.

1201
01:14:33,687 --> 01:14:37,350
Pictures are a different
medium than the stage.
She will need rehearsal...

1202
01:14:39,927 --> 01:14:44,091
Fetched y'all a mess
of crawdads, Miss Lora,
for you and yo' friends.

1203
01:14:44,164 --> 01:14:48,157
That's quite a trick,
Sarah Jane.
Where did you learn it?

1204
01:14:48,235 --> 01:14:50,669
Oh, no trick to totin',
Miss Lora.

1205
01:14:50,738 --> 01:14:52,672
I learned it
from my mammy,

1206
01:14:52,740 --> 01:14:56,676
and she learned it
from old massa 'fore
she belonged to you.

1207
01:15:00,581 --> 01:15:02,515
Well...
Excuse me.

1208
01:15:07,521 --> 01:15:09,455
Another drink,
Sr. Romano?

1209
01:15:11,325 --> 01:15:14,761
Sarah Jane,
why did you do that?

1210
01:15:14,828 --> 01:15:17,262
What's the matter
with you?

1211
01:15:17,331 --> 01:15:20,596
Annie, did you see
what she did?
I heard her.

1212
01:15:20,668 --> 01:15:24,104
You and my mother
are so anxious for me
to be colored.

1213
01:15:25,172 --> 01:15:28,608
I was going to show you
I could be.

1214
01:15:33,681 --> 01:15:35,979
You weren't being
colored.

1215
01:15:36,050 --> 01:15:37,984
You were being
childish.

1216
01:15:38,052 --> 01:15:41,988
I don't understand why
you would want to hurt
your mother or me.

1217
01:15:42,056 --> 01:15:44,991
I told her
she has to be patient.

1218
01:15:45,059 --> 01:15:46,993
Things will work out.
How?

1219
01:15:48,962 --> 01:15:52,329
Miss Lora, you don't know
what it means to be...

1220
01:15:52,399 --> 01:15:54,333
different.

1221
01:15:54,401 --> 01:15:59,065
Have I ever treated you
as if you were different?
Has Susie? Has anyone here?

1222
01:16:01,375 --> 01:16:03,343
No.

1223
01:16:03,410 --> 01:16:05,344
You've been wonderful,
but...

1224
01:16:05,412 --> 01:16:08,347
Then don't ever do this
to us again.

1225
01:16:08,415 --> 01:16:10,280
Or to yourself.

1226
01:16:12,019 --> 01:16:14,453
It won't solve anything,
Sarah Jane.

1227
01:16:32,840 --> 01:16:34,774
Mama?

1228
01:16:36,009 --> 01:16:37,943
Oh, please.

1229
01:16:39,346 --> 01:16:41,280
Try to understand.

1230
01:16:42,516 --> 01:16:45,610
l-I didn't mean
to hurt you.

1231
01:16:45,686 --> 01:16:47,620
I love you.

1232
01:16:47,688 --> 01:16:50,282
Oh, I know, baby.

1233
01:16:50,357 --> 01:16:54,487
You're just like
a puppy that's been
cooped up too much.

1234
01:16:55,662 --> 01:16:59,598
That's why I wanted you
to go to the party.

1235
01:17:01,034 --> 01:17:03,468
Oh, Mama.

1236
01:17:03,537 --> 01:17:05,971
Don't you see
that won't help?

1237
01:17:25,928 --> 01:17:27,862
<i>[Allen]</i>
<i>Lora, wait a minute. </i>

1238
01:17:27,930 --> 01:17:30,865
<i>[Lora]</i>
<i>I didn't mean the whole thing. </i>
<i>I said... </i>

1239
01:17:30,933 --> 01:17:33,868
<i>[Allen]</i>
<i>Sr. Romano, she won't</i>
<i>need rehearsal. </i>

1240
01:17:42,511 --> 01:17:45,105
Frankie, you're late.

1241
01:17:46,182 --> 01:17:48,616
I thought
you'd never get here.

1242
01:17:50,352 --> 01:17:53,287
Let's walk down
by the river.

1243
01:17:53,355 --> 01:17:55,448
I wanna talk to you.

1244
01:17:55,524 --> 01:17:57,458
We can talk here.

1245
01:17:57,526 --> 01:18:00,324
Frankie, I'm...

1246
01:18:00,396 --> 01:18:02,330
I'm having
trouble at home.

1247
01:18:02,398 --> 01:18:05,299
Your mother?
Yes.

1248
01:18:05,367 --> 01:18:10,134
Frankie, you said
you wanted to take
a job in Jersey.

1249
01:18:10,206 --> 01:18:12,106
Couldn't we run away?

1250
01:18:12,174 --> 01:18:15,575
I'd do anything
to be with you,
anything.

1251
01:18:15,644 --> 01:18:18,078
That's not a bad idea.

1252
01:18:18,147 --> 01:18:21,082
That's not
a bad idea at all.

1253
01:18:21,150 --> 01:18:23,243
Just tell me
one thing.
Yes?

1254
01:18:23,319 --> 01:18:25,253
Is it true?

1255
01:18:25,321 --> 01:18:27,255
Is what true?

1256
01:18:27,323 --> 01:18:29,757
Is your mother
a nigger?

1257
01:18:29,825 --> 01:18:32,089
Tell me.

1258
01:18:32,161 --> 01:18:34,595
Tell me!
What difference
does it make?
You love me!

1259
01:18:34,663 --> 01:18:37,598
All the kids talking
behind my back!
Is it true?

1260
01:18:37,666 --> 01:18:39,600
No!
Are you black?

1261
01:18:39,668 --> 01:18:41,602
I'm as white as you!
You're lying!

1262
01:18:41,670 --> 01:18:43,604
No, I'm not!
You're lying!

1263
01:18:43,672 --> 01:18:46,835
No, I'm not!
I'm not!
You are! You're lying!

1264
01:18:46,909 --> 01:18:49,173
Don't hit me!

1265
01:18:49,245 --> 01:18:52,009
[Screaming]

1266
01:18:52,081 --> 01:18:55,107
[Groaning]

1267
01:18:55,184 --> 01:18:57,118
I'm not.

1268
01:18:57,186 --> 01:18:59,120
[Weeping]

1269
01:19:17,840 --> 01:19:19,774
Mmm.

1270
01:19:19,842 --> 01:19:22,276
Oh, that felt so good.

1271
01:19:22,344 --> 01:19:25,279
And I'm glad
the guests have gone.

1272
01:19:25,347 --> 01:19:28,282
I'm glad you're not
going to Italy.
So am I.

1273
01:19:28,350 --> 01:19:31,285
Felluci wanted me
in Rome in one week.

1274
01:19:31,353 --> 01:19:34,789
But I won't miss
Susie's graduation,
not for anything.

1275
01:19:34,857 --> 01:19:36,916
You know,
I can't believe it.

1276
01:19:36,992 --> 01:19:39,927
Susie and Sarah Jane
all grown up.

1277
01:19:41,497 --> 01:19:44,933
You and I have gone
through a lot together,
haven't we?

1278
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:48,436
The years are flyin'.
I'm getting old.

1279
01:19:48,504 --> 01:19:51,871
You never sounded
so solemn before.

1280
01:19:51,940 --> 01:19:56,001
Don't you feel well,
Annie?
Oh, just
a little tired.

1281
01:19:56,078 --> 01:19:59,013
Well, do you need anything?
Any money?

1282
01:19:59,081 --> 01:20:02,016
No, Miss Lora.
Thanks to you,
I'm well fixed.

1283
01:20:02,084 --> 01:20:05,019
I've plenty to send
Sarah Jane to college,

1284
01:20:05,087 --> 01:20:09,023
something set aside for her,
and enough for my funeral.
Oh, Annie.

1285
01:20:09,091 --> 01:20:11,525
That funeral again.
Well, I'm gettin' on.

1286
01:20:11,593 --> 01:20:14,528
That's the one thing
I've always wanted
to splurge on.

1287
01:20:14,596 --> 01:20:16,530
I really want it elegant.

1288
01:20:16,598 --> 01:20:21,535
Got it written down the way I
want it to be, all the friends
I'd like to have there.

1289
01:20:21,603 --> 01:20:24,538
It never occurred to me
that you had many friends.

1290
01:20:24,606 --> 01:20:29,043
You never have any visit you.
I know lots of people.
Oh, hundreds.

1291
01:20:29,111 --> 01:20:32,046
Really?
I belong to
the baptist church.

1292
01:20:32,114 --> 01:20:36,312
And I belong
to several lodges too.
I didn't know.

1293
01:20:36,385 --> 01:20:39,445
[Chuckles]
Miss Lora,
you never asked.

1294
01:20:40,622 --> 01:20:43,056
Mama, Annie, quick!
It's Sarah Jane!

1295
01:20:43,125 --> 01:20:45,059
Oh!

1296
01:20:50,598 --> 01:20:53,931
Sarah Jane!
Oh, my baby!

1297
01:20:54,002 --> 01:20:57,199
Get some water and towels.
What happened, baby?
What happened?

1298
01:20:57,271 --> 01:21:00,297
Leave me alone.
Honey, who did this
to you?

1299
01:21:00,375 --> 01:21:02,309
Tell me!
Leave me alone!

1300
01:21:02,377 --> 01:21:04,311
You've got to
tell me!
Who was it?

1301
01:21:05,780 --> 01:21:09,181
It was her boyfriend.
Boyfriend?

1302
01:21:09,250 --> 01:21:12,777
Yes. He found out
I'm not white,

1303
01:21:12,854 --> 01:21:15,846
because you keep telling
the world I'm your daughter.

1304
01:21:15,923 --> 01:21:18,619
Anything you can spoil,
you spoil!

1305
01:21:18,693 --> 01:21:21,059
Stop that.
Stop it!

1306
01:21:21,129 --> 01:21:23,222
Don't you talk
to your mother like that.

1307
01:21:23,297 --> 01:21:26,733
I told you.
Lies don't help none.

1308
01:21:26,801 --> 01:21:28,735
This always happens
when you lie.

1309
01:21:28,803 --> 01:21:31,237
It wouldn't if you
weren't always around!

1310
01:21:34,308 --> 01:21:36,242
[Door Slams]

1311
01:21:38,846 --> 01:21:40,473
Thank you.

1312
01:21:40,548 --> 01:21:43,415
Are you sure Annie
will make it in time?
Honey, you know Annie.

1313
01:21:43,484 --> 01:21:45,952
If she says she will,
she will.
[Chuckling]

1314
01:21:46,020 --> 01:21:48,284
Oh, Mama, I'm so happy.

1315
01:21:48,356 --> 01:21:52,292
You know, I never really
believed you'd be here.
<i>[Laughing]</i>

1316
01:21:52,360 --> 01:21:54,294
Are you sorry
about the picture?

1317
01:21:56,197 --> 01:22:00,031
I'm only sorry I couldn't
bring your present with me,
but he's a little bit too big.

1318
01:22:00,101 --> 01:22:02,035
He? Who's he?
Who's too big?

1319
01:22:02,103 --> 01:22:04,799
That thoroughbred
you told me about,
the one you love so?
Yeah?

1320
01:22:04,872 --> 01:22:07,432
Well, he's waiting
for you at home.
You mean he's mine?

1321
01:22:07,508 --> 01:22:09,476
Yes!
Oh, Mama, thank you!

1322
01:22:09,544 --> 01:22:11,705
Happy graduation, angel.
<i>[Car Horn Honks]</i>

1323
01:22:11,779 --> 01:22:13,713
[Honks]

1324
01:22:15,950 --> 01:22:18,077
Oh, Mama, look!
It's Annie.

1325
01:22:20,188 --> 01:22:22,418
<i>[Susie]</i>
<i>And Steve! </i>

1326
01:22:22,490 --> 01:22:24,617
Steve!

1327
01:22:25,693 --> 01:22:28,287
<i>[Susie]</i>
<i>Hi! </i>
Susie!

1328
01:22:28,362 --> 01:22:30,956
Oh, and Annie,
I'm so glad you've made it.

1329
01:22:31,032 --> 01:22:32,966
Steve, you're such
a darling to come.

1330
01:22:33,034 --> 01:22:37,300
I meant it when I said
I wouldn't miss it for the...
Lora!

1331
01:22:38,539 --> 01:22:41,667
Hello, Steve.
I thought you were
in Italy.

1332
01:22:41,742 --> 01:22:44,734
Annie, why didn't
you tell me?
Slipped my mind, I'm afraid.

1333
01:22:44,812 --> 01:22:47,007
This came for you
this mornin'.
Oh.

1334
01:22:47,081 --> 01:22:49,515
Honey, Sarah Jane's
much better.
I'm glad.

1335
01:22:49,584 --> 01:22:52,018
She's sorry
she couldn't come,
but she sends her love.

1336
01:22:52,086 --> 01:22:55,453
I think I'm gonna faint.
This is the most exciting
day of my entire life.

1337
01:22:55,523 --> 01:22:57,650
I never expected
you'd all be here.

1338
01:22:57,725 --> 01:23:00,523
Oh, it's...
It's from Felluci.

1339
01:23:00,595 --> 01:23:04,031
He still wants me
for the part, and he'll
wait after all.

1340
01:23:04,098 --> 01:23:07,556
<i>He's even made</i>
<i>my plane reservations. </i>
<i>I'm to leave in two weeks. </i>

1341
01:23:07,635 --> 01:23:10,229
Two weeks?
Oh, Mama.

1342
01:23:10,304 --> 01:23:14,604
Oh! At least that time
will be ours together.

1343
01:23:14,675 --> 01:23:18,611
Oh, don't look like that.
Felluci agreed to my terms.

1344
01:23:18,679 --> 01:23:22,274
I can't turn him down now.
I know, Mother,
I know.

1345
01:23:22,350 --> 01:23:25,615
Look, honey, your mama
feels worse than you.
[Clapping]

1346
01:23:25,686 --> 01:23:29,554
Girls, the exercises
are beginning. Come on!

1347
01:23:29,624 --> 01:23:31,558
Darling.

1348
01:23:38,199 --> 01:23:40,258
When do you leave, Steve?

1349
01:23:40,334 --> 01:23:43,633
I don't know when I'll
be able to get away now.
Oh.

1350
01:23:43,704 --> 01:23:45,831
Would you do me a favor?

1351
01:23:45,907 --> 01:23:50,173
Will you look after my child
for me while I'm gone?
Please?

1352
01:23:50,244 --> 01:23:53,407
I can think of nothing
I'd like better.

1353
01:23:53,481 --> 01:23:56,416
<music> [Jazz Pop]
<i>[Horse Whinnying]</i>

1354
01:24:03,090 --> 01:24:05,581
All right?
Fine. Let's ride
down to the river.

1355
01:24:08,429 --> 01:24:10,363
Thank you.

1356
01:24:11,666 --> 01:24:14,100
<i><music>[Continues]</i>

1357
01:24:35,690 --> 01:24:37,624
Isn't this fun?

1358
01:24:37,692 --> 01:24:40,388
I wrote Mother last week
and told her you were riding
like Audie Murphy.

1359
01:24:40,461 --> 01:24:42,622
I'll wear my six-shooters
tomorrow morning.

1360
01:24:42,697 --> 01:24:44,756
And your black tie
tomorrow night at Bocce's.

1361
01:24:44,832 --> 01:24:47,266
Did we make it
definitely tomorrow?
You said Monday night.

1362
01:24:47,335 --> 01:24:49,769
I hope you won't
be disappointed.
It's nothing glamorous.

1363
01:24:49,837 --> 01:24:53,637
Disappointed with you, Steve?
Never. Come on, I'll race you
back to the old mill.

1364
01:24:57,745 --> 01:25:00,179
<i><music>[Orchestra]</i>

1365
01:25:05,253 --> 01:25:07,517
I hope you won't
be disappointed.

1366
01:25:07,588 --> 01:25:09,818
Oh, no. I think
it's romantic.

1367
01:25:09,890 --> 01:25:12,324
Good evening.
A table for two?
Please.

1368
01:25:18,566 --> 01:25:22,798
What a wonderful place
to end a perfect evening.
I'll have cognac and...

1369
01:25:22,870 --> 01:25:25,805
Could I have one too?
Just once?
Mm-mmm.

1370
01:25:25,873 --> 01:25:28,034
Maybe a little wine?
No.

1371
01:25:28,109 --> 01:25:31,977
Coke. You don't want them
to lose their license,
do you?

1372
01:25:32,046 --> 01:25:34,776
No, of course not,
but...
Shall we dance?

1373
01:25:34,849 --> 01:25:37,283
Dance?
Oh, I'd love to, Steve.

1374
01:25:42,023 --> 01:25:45,220
You know,
you're the only one that
I can talk seriously with.

1375
01:25:45,293 --> 01:25:48,660
What about Annie?
I thought she was everybody's
Rock of Gibraltar.

1376
01:25:48,729 --> 01:25:52,893
She still treats me
like I was a child, as if
I were just out of rompers.

1377
01:25:52,967 --> 01:25:55,902
You don't.
Well, you're
almost a woman.

1378
01:25:55,970 --> 01:25:58,165
Almost?

1379
01:25:58,239 --> 01:26:02,767
Anytime you have anything
serious on your mind,
you try it out on me.

1380
01:26:02,843 --> 01:26:07,405
Well, l...
I do have a problem
that's been bothering me.

1381
01:26:07,481 --> 01:26:09,676
Let's have it.

1382
01:26:09,750 --> 01:26:12,412
No. Maybe I shouldn't.

1383
01:26:12,486 --> 01:26:14,511
I'll bet I know
what it's about.

1384
01:26:14,588 --> 01:26:16,556
You do?

1385
01:26:16,624 --> 01:26:19,115
Boys.
Oh, no.

1386
01:26:19,193 --> 01:26:22,424
You were teasing me.
Yes.

1387
01:26:22,496 --> 01:26:27,092
Steve, what's the proper
age for people to...

1388
01:26:27,168 --> 01:26:29,136
Well, to get married?

1389
01:26:29,203 --> 01:26:32,570
That is a problem.
I'm no authority.

1390
01:26:32,640 --> 01:26:35,632
Isn't being in love enough?

1391
01:26:35,710 --> 01:26:38,543
As long as it's
on both sides.

1392
01:26:38,612 --> 01:26:42,104
But then at your age,
there's always
the possibility of...

1393
01:26:42,183 --> 01:26:44,583
being in love with love.
No.

1394
01:26:44,652 --> 01:26:47,120
No, it's real.
I am.

1395
01:26:47,188 --> 01:26:49,122
In love?
Mm-hmm.

1396
01:26:49,190 --> 01:26:51,988
Wanna talk about it?
Well, l...

1397
01:26:52,059 --> 01:26:53,993
No. Not yet.

1398
01:26:55,229 --> 01:26:58,198
<i><music>[Stops]</i>
<i>[Applause]</i>

1399
01:26:58,265 --> 01:27:02,326
Sometimes though, l...
I feel awfully lonely.

1400
01:27:02,403 --> 01:27:05,429
Love is always a little
lonely in the beginning,

1401
01:27:05,506 --> 01:27:08,907
especially when you're
not sure the other party
feels as you do.

1402
01:27:08,976 --> 01:27:11,945
But it's heavenly, though.
Don't you agree?
I do.

1403
01:27:12,012 --> 01:27:14,446
Marvelous.
No substitute for it.

1404
01:27:16,983 --> 01:27:19,918
Oh, I'm so glad I'm alive.
I've never been so glad before.

1405
01:27:19,986 --> 01:27:22,420
Every time we've been together,
it's been just perfect!

1406
01:27:22,489 --> 01:27:26,084
You ought to go out more
with friends your own age.
Than go out with Steve?

1407
01:27:26,159 --> 01:27:30,994
Annie, you can't believe
how much we have in common.
<i>[Car Horn Honks]</i>

1408
01:27:31,064 --> 01:27:33,692
Oh, it's Steve!
Now, you're not going out
without a coat.

1409
01:27:33,767 --> 01:27:36,702
I was going to
borrow one of Mother's.
Steve's seen all of mine.

1410
01:27:36,770 --> 01:27:39,705
Sarah Jane bought
herself a new one.
You can wear hers.

1411
01:27:39,773 --> 01:27:42,708
<i>[Honking Continues]</i>
Oh, I'll be right down!

1412
01:27:44,277 --> 01:27:46,711
Annie, I haven't seen
Sarah Jane in weeks.

1413
01:27:46,780 --> 01:27:49,408
Does she like that new job
in New York?

1414
01:27:49,482 --> 01:27:51,473
Oh, yes.
Thank you.

1415
01:27:51,551 --> 01:27:54,111
The Head Librarian
thinks she's so good,

1416
01:27:54,187 --> 01:27:57,452
why, she even gave her
a raise.
<i>That's wonderful! </i>

1417
01:27:57,524 --> 01:28:02,120
She just wrote me the other
day and she said that...
<i>[Honking Continues]</i>

1418
01:28:02,195 --> 01:28:05,130
Oh, don't wait up for me.
I'm going to be terribly late.

1419
01:28:05,198 --> 01:28:07,132
Good night, sweetie.

1420
01:28:09,035 --> 01:28:10,969
Harry's Club?

1421
01:28:21,581 --> 01:28:24,175
Hope I didn't keep you
waiting too long, Steve.

1422
01:28:24,250 --> 01:28:28,152
Hello?
Is this the Manhattan
Public Library?

1423
01:28:28,221 --> 01:28:31,713
[Man] Yes, it is.
May I speak to Miss
Sarah Jane Johnson, please?

1424
01:28:31,791 --> 01:28:33,782
I'm sorry.
The library's closed.

1425
01:28:33,860 --> 01:28:36,420
Yes, I know, but she's
on a late shift.

1426
01:28:36,496 --> 01:28:38,862
Reclassifying books
after hours, she said.

1427
01:28:38,932 --> 01:28:41,196
There's no one here
by that name.

1428
01:28:41,267 --> 01:28:44,202
You have no one there
by that name?
No.

1429
01:28:44,270 --> 01:28:47,569
Are you sure?
Absolutely sure?

1430
01:28:47,640 --> 01:28:50,234
Yes, I'm sure.
No one.

1431
01:28:50,310 --> 01:28:52,471
I see.

1432
01:28:52,545 --> 01:28:55,605
Well, thank you very much.

1433
01:28:55,682 --> 01:28:57,616
Thank you.

1434
01:29:03,857 --> 01:29:06,291
<i><music>[Jazz Combo, Faint]</i>

1435
01:29:19,639 --> 01:29:22,073
<i><music>[Jazz Combo, Loud]</i>

1436
01:29:27,881 --> 01:29:29,815
Can I help you, lady?

1437
01:29:29,883 --> 01:29:32,909
Is there a girl named
Sarah Jane Johnson
working here?

1438
01:29:32,986 --> 01:29:35,511
Never heard of her.
Two?

1439
01:29:35,588 --> 01:29:38,182
<i><music>[Ends]</i>
<i>[Applause]</i>

1440
01:29:47,267 --> 01:29:51,795
<music> The loneliest word
I've heard of is empty <music>

1441
01:29:51,871 --> 01:29:56,706
<music> Anything empty is sad <music>

1442
01:29:56,776 --> 01:30:02,476
<music> An empty purse
can make a good girl bad <music>

1443
01:30:02,549 --> 01:30:04,881
<music> You hear me, Dad <music>

1444
01:30:04,951 --> 01:30:07,511
[Laughing]
<music> The loneliest word <music>

1445
01:30:07,587 --> 01:30:09,817
<i><music>I've heard of is empty <music></i>

1446
01:30:09,889 --> 01:30:14,883
<music> Empty things
make me so mad <music>
[Laughing]

1447
01:30:14,961 --> 01:30:20,331
<music> So fill me up
with what I formerly had <music>

1448
01:30:23,703 --> 01:30:26,331
<music> Now, Venus, you know <music>

1449
01:30:26,406 --> 01:30:28,567
<music> Was loaded with charms <music>

1450
01:30:28,641 --> 01:30:33,044
<music> And look at
what happened to her <music>

1451
01:30:33,112 --> 01:30:37,845
<music> Waitin' around
she's minus two arms <music>

1452
01:30:37,917 --> 01:30:40,511
<music> Could happen to me
no, sir <music>

1453
01:30:42,589 --> 01:30:47,026
<music> Now is the time
to fill what is empty <music>

1454
01:30:47,093 --> 01:30:51,689
<music> Fill my life
brim full of charms <music>

1455
01:30:51,764 --> 01:30:56,292
<music> Help me refill
these empty <music>

1456
01:30:56,369 --> 01:31:01,363
<music> Empty, empty arms <music>

1457
01:31:03,176 --> 01:31:06,236
<i><music>[Combo Ends]</i>
[Cheering]

1458
01:31:06,312 --> 01:31:08,246
<i><music>[Combo Resumes]</i>

1459
01:31:16,122 --> 01:31:19,614
<i>I thought you were great</i>
<i>tonight, really great. </i>
Thank you.

1460
01:31:19,692 --> 01:31:22,058
Where do you go
when you run out of here
every night?

1461
01:31:22,128 --> 01:31:24,358
You got a boyfriend?
Could be.

1462
01:31:24,430 --> 01:31:27,365
[Chuckling]
If you weren't such a cute...
Sarah Jane Johnson!

1463
01:31:27,433 --> 01:31:32,370
- You put your clothes on
and get out of this place.
- Say, who is this character?

1464
01:31:33,740 --> 01:31:37,540
I don't know.
I've never seen her
before in my life.

1465
01:31:37,610 --> 01:31:41,603
Quit lyin'. You told me
you had a respectable job
in the library.

1466
01:31:41,681 --> 01:31:44,514
Hey, what's going on here?

1467
01:31:44,584 --> 01:31:46,950
Well, she must be crazy.

1468
01:31:47,020 --> 01:31:50,012
Tell her
my name's Judy Brand.
Make her go away.

1469
01:31:50,089 --> 01:31:52,250
Look, lady,
why don't you blow?

1470
01:31:52,325 --> 01:31:55,692
You'd better keep out
of this. This girl here
is my daughter.

1471
01:31:55,762 --> 01:31:58,356
And if you don't tell her
to go home with me,
her mother,

1472
01:31:58,431 --> 01:32:02,367
<i>I'll have the law on you. </i>
Your mother?

1473
01:32:02,435 --> 01:32:04,369
Well, I'll be.

1474
01:32:05,505 --> 01:32:08,770
<i>[Door Slams]</i>
Go on, beat it.

1475
01:32:08,841 --> 01:32:10,775
She's through, anyway.

1476
01:32:26,759 --> 01:32:28,693
Sarah Jane.

1477
01:32:28,761 --> 01:32:30,695
What did you
expect me to do...

1478
01:32:30,763 --> 01:32:34,062
when I find you dancing
in that lowdown dive?

1479
01:32:34,133 --> 01:32:37,227
If it ever got back
to the teachers' college...

1480
01:32:37,303 --> 01:32:41,637
that you were mixed up
in such a place,
they would never let you in.

1481
01:32:41,708 --> 01:32:44,871
I wouldn't be
found dead in a colored
teachers' college.

1482
01:32:44,944 --> 01:32:49,074
Please, come home!
<i>[Horn Honks]</i>

1483
01:32:49,148 --> 01:32:51,776
We'll have some coffee
and we'll talk about this.

1484
01:32:51,851 --> 01:32:54,945
Honey, nobody's all right
about anything,

1485
01:32:55,021 --> 01:32:56,955
and nobody's all wrong.

1486
01:32:57,023 --> 01:32:59,514
If you don't want to
be a teacher, all right.

1487
01:32:59,592 --> 01:33:02,026
We'll talk about
what you want to be.

1488
01:33:02,095 --> 01:33:06,031
Honey, Miss Lora gets home
from Italy in the mornin'
and I'm sure...

1489
01:33:06,099 --> 01:33:08,033
Sarah Jane.

1490
01:33:09,268 --> 01:33:11,702
Sarah Jane!

1491
01:33:11,771 --> 01:33:14,535
Oh. Ooh, dear.

1492
01:33:24,851 --> 01:33:27,285
[Sobs]

1493
01:33:34,093 --> 01:33:36,027
Oh, Susie, darling!

1494
01:33:38,030 --> 01:33:39,964
All the flowers!

1495
01:33:41,200 --> 01:33:43,134
Oh, it's wonderful.

1496
01:33:44,803 --> 01:33:46,998
I was never so glad
to be home.

1497
01:33:47,072 --> 01:33:49,006
Annie was up
at the crack of dawn.

1498
01:33:49,074 --> 01:33:51,907
Where is she?

1499
01:33:51,977 --> 01:33:55,003
Well, I don't know.
Annie!

1500
01:33:55,080 --> 01:33:58,675
Annie!
That's funny. She was
so anxious to see you.

1501
01:33:59,885 --> 01:34:01,819
Annie?

1502
01:34:03,555 --> 01:34:06,183
Annie, what's the matter?

1503
01:34:06,258 --> 01:34:08,192
What happened?

1504
01:34:08,260 --> 01:34:10,194
Is it Sarah Jane?

1505
01:34:12,231 --> 01:34:15,223
"Mama, if you really
want to be kind,

1506
01:34:15,300 --> 01:34:17,928
"really a mother,
don't try to find me.

1507
01:34:18,003 --> 01:34:21,530
"Just pretend that I died
or was never born.

1508
01:34:21,607 --> 01:34:25,099
"This is my life and I'm going
to live it my way.

1509
01:34:25,177 --> 01:34:26,940
Sarah Jane."

1510
01:34:28,113 --> 01:34:30,047
Darling, I'm sorry.

1511
01:34:30,115 --> 01:34:32,276
We'll find her
and bring her back.

1512
01:34:32,351 --> 01:34:34,819
No, Miss Lora.

1513
01:34:34,887 --> 01:34:38,880
It's her life and I'm done
with interfering.

1514
01:34:38,957 --> 01:34:41,949
All I'd like to know somehow
is where she is,

1515
01:34:42,027 --> 01:34:45,053
so if she should ever need
anything, I can help her.

1516
01:34:45,130 --> 01:34:47,621
Do you have any idea
where she might have gone?

1517
01:34:47,699 --> 01:34:50,998
No, ma'am.
I'll bet Steve will know
what to do. I'll call him.

1518
01:34:51,070 --> 01:34:53,004
All right.

1519
01:34:54,073 --> 01:34:56,667
You lie down for a while.

1520
01:34:56,742 --> 01:34:59,677
We're going to take care
of you for a change.

1521
01:35:04,716 --> 01:35:07,810
Hello, Steve?
Yes.

1522
01:35:07,886 --> 01:35:10,320
Susie.
Let me have it.

1523
01:35:11,790 --> 01:35:15,191
Hello?
No, this isn't Susie.

1524
01:35:15,260 --> 01:35:18,752
That's right.
Oh, a few moments ago.

1525
01:35:18,831 --> 01:35:21,698
Oh, it was wonderful.
Yes.

1526
01:35:21,767 --> 01:35:25,134
And thank you for taking
such good care of my child.

1527
01:35:25,204 --> 01:35:27,138
[Laughing]
Yes, she is.

1528
01:35:27,206 --> 01:35:31,336
What's he saying about me?
He thinks you're as cute
as a button, and you are.

1529
01:35:31,410 --> 01:35:33,674
Only, Steve,

1530
01:35:33,745 --> 01:35:35,975
something dreadful
has happened.

1531
01:35:37,049 --> 01:35:39,540
When?

1532
01:35:39,618 --> 01:35:41,984
No, I'll put a detective
agency on it...

1533
01:35:42,054 --> 01:35:44,716
and I'll report
the moment I hear anything.

1534
01:35:44,790 --> 01:35:46,724
Good-bye.

1535
01:35:49,294 --> 01:35:53,060
Then under the name
of Linda Carroll,
she got herself a job...

1536
01:35:53,132 --> 01:35:55,828
in the chorus line
at the Moulin Rouge
in Hollywood.

1537
01:35:55,901 --> 01:35:58,995
Where is she living?
At a motel nearby.

1538
01:36:00,105 --> 01:36:02,665
Thanks, Mr. Steve.
I'm going out there.

1539
01:36:02,741 --> 01:36:05,505
No, Annie, you can't.
You're not well enough.

1540
01:36:05,577 --> 01:36:07,636
I'll go get her myself.
No.

1541
01:36:07,713 --> 01:36:10,238
Miss Lora, I have to go.

1542
01:36:10,315 --> 01:36:13,648
I've just got to see
my baby once more.

1543
01:36:13,719 --> 01:36:17,280
All right, Annie.
I'll have my office make
your train reservations.

1544
01:36:17,356 --> 01:36:20,325
Thanks, but I'm not
going by train.

1545
01:36:20,392 --> 01:36:22,553
I'm going to fly.

1546
01:36:22,628 --> 01:36:24,562
I'm in a hurry.

1547
01:36:34,773 --> 01:36:37,207
<i><music>[Jazz Band]</i>

1548
01:37:12,077 --> 01:37:14,511
<i><music>[Continues]</i>

1549
01:38:39,798 --> 01:38:42,232
[Applauding]

1550
01:38:52,144 --> 01:38:55,136
<i><music>[Song Ends]</i>

1551
01:38:55,213 --> 01:38:57,147
What's up, honey?
<i><music>[Band]</i>

1552
01:38:57,215 --> 01:39:00,810
Oh. I don't know.
Just a funny feeling.

1553
01:39:00,886 --> 01:39:03,548
Don't forget the guys
are picking us up at 12:30.

1554
01:39:03,622 --> 01:39:06,557
I'll rush to the motel
and change. See you there.

1555
01:39:06,625 --> 01:39:09,150
<i><music>[Continues]</i>

1556
01:39:21,673 --> 01:39:24,107
<i>[Knock On Door]</i>
Door's open.

1557
01:39:26,545 --> 01:39:28,843
I'll be ready
in a minute.

1558
01:39:28,914 --> 01:39:31,474
I hope they're not here...

1559
01:39:31,550 --> 01:39:35,179
Now, don't be mad, honey.
Nobody saw me.

1560
01:39:36,888 --> 01:39:38,822
It <i>was</i> you.

1561
01:39:40,425 --> 01:39:42,859
You <i>were</i> there tonight.

1562
01:39:42,928 --> 01:39:44,862
Why can't you leave me alone?

1563
01:39:44,930 --> 01:39:48,127
I tried, Sarah Jane.

1564
01:39:48,200 --> 01:39:50,293
You'll never know
how hard I tried.

1565
01:39:50,369 --> 01:39:52,894
Well,

1566
01:39:52,971 --> 01:39:54,905
I might as well pack.

1567
01:39:57,409 --> 01:40:00,970
Look, baby...
I suppose you've been
to the boss,

1568
01:40:01,046 --> 01:40:03,571
Iost me my job,
my friends...

1569
01:40:03,648 --> 01:40:06,242
I've been no place.
I didn't come to bother you.

1570
01:40:06,318 --> 01:40:08,650
Well, you won't.
Not ever again.

1571
01:40:08,720 --> 01:40:11,382
Spoil things for me here
and I'll go somewhere else.

1572
01:40:11,456 --> 01:40:14,323
And I'll keep on going
until you're so tired...

1573
01:40:14,393 --> 01:40:16,987
Baby, I am tired.

1574
01:40:17,062 --> 01:40:20,361
I'm as tired
as I ever want to be.

1575
01:40:20,432 --> 01:40:24,664
You mind if I sit down?
Yes, I do.

1576
01:40:26,738 --> 01:40:30,003
Somebody's coming.
That's why the door
was unlocked.

1577
01:40:30,075 --> 01:40:32,407
I'll only stay a minute.

1578
01:40:32,477 --> 01:40:36,777
I just want to look at you.
That's why I came.

1579
01:40:36,848 --> 01:40:40,784
Are you happy here, honey?
Are you finding what
you really want?

1580
01:40:40,852 --> 01:40:43,582
I'm somebody else.

1581
01:40:43,655 --> 01:40:46,681
I'm white. White!

1582
01:40:47,893 --> 01:40:50,691
White!

1583
01:40:50,762 --> 01:40:53,196
[Crying]

1584
01:40:55,734 --> 01:40:57,827
Does that answer you?

1585
01:40:57,903 --> 01:40:59,837
I guess so.

1586
01:40:59,905 --> 01:41:02,430
Then please, Mama,
will you go...

1587
01:41:02,507 --> 01:41:04,634
and never do this again?

1588
01:41:04,709 --> 01:41:07,610
And if by accident,
if we should ever pass
on the street,

1589
01:41:07,679 --> 01:41:09,613
please don't recognize me.

1590
01:41:11,016 --> 01:41:14,383
I won't, Sarah Jane.
I promise.

1591
01:41:14,453 --> 01:41:17,422
I settled all that
in my mind.

1592
01:41:17,489 --> 01:41:20,458
There's just one thing
I wish from you.
What?

1593
01:41:20,525 --> 01:41:23,050
If you're ever in trouble,

1594
01:41:23,128 --> 01:41:25,722
if you ever need
anything at all,

1595
01:41:25,797 --> 01:41:27,788
if you ever want
to come home...

1596
01:41:27,866 --> 01:41:30,767
and you shouldn't be able
to get in touch with me,

1597
01:41:30,836 --> 01:41:33,964
will you let
Miss Lora know?
Yes.

1598
01:41:34,039 --> 01:41:36,633
Yes, anything.
Now will you go?

1599
01:41:36,708 --> 01:41:39,302
That wasn't all I wanted,
honey.

1600
01:41:39,377 --> 01:41:41,572
That was only part of it.

1601
01:41:41,646 --> 01:41:43,637
What's the rest?

1602
01:41:43,715 --> 01:41:46,548
I'd like to hold you
in my arms once more...

1603
01:41:46,618 --> 01:41:48,552
like you were
still my baby.

1604
01:41:49,921 --> 01:41:52,913
All right, Mama.
All right.

1605
01:41:52,991 --> 01:41:55,221
Oh, Sarah Jane.

1606
01:41:55,293 --> 01:41:57,727
[Crying]
Oh, my baby!

1607
01:41:59,130 --> 01:42:02,065
My beautiful,
beautiful baby!

1608
01:42:02,133 --> 01:42:04,658
Oh!
[Continues Crying]

1609
01:42:04,736 --> 01:42:09,139
I love you so much.
Nothin' you ever do
can stop that.

1610
01:42:09,207 --> 01:42:11,698
Oh, Mama!

1611
01:42:11,776 --> 01:42:15,212
Oh, my baby.
Mama. Mama.

1612
01:42:16,548 --> 01:42:19,039
Oh, my baby.

1613
01:42:19,117 --> 01:42:21,051
<i>[Knock On Door]</i>

1614
01:42:21,119 --> 01:42:24,714
[Sniffling]
Come on, Linda,
they're waiting.

1615
01:42:26,925 --> 01:42:30,952
Listen, if you're the new maid,
I want to report that my shower
is full of ants.

1616
01:42:31,029 --> 01:42:34,897
Oh, I'm sorry, miss.
That must be very uncomfortable.

1617
01:42:34,966 --> 01:42:39,403
But I just happened to be
in town and dropped in
to see Miss Linda.

1618
01:42:39,471 --> 01:42:41,735
I used to take care of her.

1619
01:42:43,341 --> 01:42:47,607
Well, I guess I'll
be running along.

1620
01:42:47,679 --> 01:42:51,115
My plane's leaving
in a little while,
Miss Linda.

1621
01:42:53,351 --> 01:42:56,320
[Whispering]
Good-bye, honey.

1622
01:42:56,388 --> 01:42:59,846
You take good care
of yourself.

1623
01:42:59,925 --> 01:43:02,086
Good-bye.

1624
01:43:02,160 --> 01:43:04,094
[Whispers]
Mama.

1625
01:43:09,601 --> 01:43:12,297
Well! Get you.

1626
01:43:12,370 --> 01:43:16,204
[Southern Accent]
So, honey child,
you had a mammy.

1627
01:43:16,274 --> 01:43:18,208
Yes.

1628
01:43:19,444 --> 01:43:21,378
All my life.

1629
01:43:31,451 --> 01:43:33,510
Hello, Steve.

1630
01:43:33,587 --> 01:43:35,521
Hello, Lora.

1631
01:43:37,024 --> 01:43:39,788
Some of my girlfriends
get embarrassed
when their mothers...

1632
01:43:39,860 --> 01:43:42,454
wear shorts or capri pants,
things like that.

1633
01:43:42,529 --> 01:43:45,589
I really don't mind.
[Giggling]
That's very big of you.

1634
01:43:45,666 --> 01:43:49,067
I mixed you a highball,
but you only get one
before lunch.

1635
01:43:49,136 --> 01:43:51,798
Yes, ma'am.
I just had a call
from Loomis.

1636
01:43:51,872 --> 01:43:55,137
Don't say a word.
He's got a new role for you.
No, no.

1637
01:43:55,208 --> 01:43:57,142
<i>Highball? </i>
Yes.

1638
01:43:57,210 --> 01:43:59,576
No, they've flown over a print
of the Italian picture.

1639
01:43:59,646 --> 01:44:03,480
He's arranged
a special showing tonight,
and a party afterwards.

1640
01:44:03,550 --> 01:44:05,745
Darling, I'd like you
to see it too,

1641
01:44:05,819 --> 01:44:08,151
but I'm worried
about Annie.

1642
01:44:08,221 --> 01:44:11,315
Ever since she came
back from Los Angeles,
she's changed.

1643
01:44:11,391 --> 01:44:14,690
Dr. Miller's quite concerned
about her condition.

1644
01:44:14,761 --> 01:44:18,697
I think someone should stay
in the house with her tonight.
Do you mind?

1645
01:44:18,765 --> 01:44:21,825
No, of course not, Mama.
I'll see you tomorrow, Steve?

1646
01:44:21,902 --> 01:44:24,496
Sure.

1647
01:44:24,571 --> 01:44:27,506
What can we do
to help Annie, Steve?

1648
01:44:27,574 --> 01:44:31,101
There's no answer, Lora,
never has been.

1649
01:44:31,178 --> 01:44:33,112
Not for a broken heart.

1650
01:44:33,180 --> 01:44:35,614
Mmm, and I know Mother
didn't understand.

1651
01:44:35,682 --> 01:44:38,048
Oh, it was so embarrassing.
And poor Steve.

1652
01:44:38,118 --> 01:44:41,713
I mean, what could he do?
She just swept over him
like a tidal wave.

1653
01:44:41,788 --> 01:44:45,815
Honey, it's only natural
he'd like to go out
with your mother.

1654
01:44:45,892 --> 01:44:49,555
He always enjoyed her company.
You remember that.

1655
01:44:49,630 --> 01:44:51,598
But it's different now.

1656
01:44:51,665 --> 01:44:53,860
All summer long
it's been Steve and me.

1657
01:44:55,135 --> 01:44:58,730
- Annie, you know, don't you?
- Know what?

1658
01:44:58,805 --> 01:45:03,674
That I'm in love with Steve.
I've always been in love
with him and always will be.

1659
01:45:03,744 --> 01:45:06,406
Sure, Susie,

1660
01:45:06,480 --> 01:45:08,812
but like a little girl.

1661
01:45:08,882 --> 01:45:12,113
<i>No. I don't think</i>
<i>it even started like that. </i>

1662
01:45:12,185 --> 01:45:15,416
In a funny way,
I always knew.

1663
01:45:15,489 --> 01:45:19,425
Every time I thought
I liked a boy, it was because
he reminded me of Steve.

1664
01:45:19,493 --> 01:45:23,020
And then I'd stop
liking him because...

1665
01:45:23,096 --> 01:45:25,189
Because he wasn't Steve.

1666
01:46:41,108 --> 01:46:43,042
[Knocking]

1667
01:46:44,911 --> 01:46:47,539
Susie?
Are you up, darling?

1668
01:46:47,614 --> 01:46:49,673
<i>Yes. </i>

1669
01:46:49,750 --> 01:46:53,277
I just had to tell you.
I have the most wonderful news.

1670
01:46:53,353 --> 01:46:56,220
You're going to do
another picture.
No.

1671
01:46:56,289 --> 01:47:00,453
Not a picture,
not a play,
never again.

1672
01:47:00,527 --> 01:47:04,554
Oh, I know you
don't believe me.
I can't blame you.

1673
01:47:04,631 --> 01:47:08,260
Steve didn't either.
He probably won't until
our tenth anniversary.

1674
01:47:09,836 --> 01:47:11,770
A-Anniversary?

1675
01:47:11,838 --> 01:47:15,239
Oh, Steve and I have
always been in love.

1676
01:47:15,308 --> 01:47:19,711
But it seems I've never
had time for anything
but my work.

1677
01:47:19,780 --> 01:47:23,807
So I just up and proposed
that we get married.

1678
01:47:25,619 --> 01:47:29,180
<i>Well, Susie, </i>
<i>what's the matter? </i>
<i>Are you all right? </i>

1679
01:47:29,256 --> 01:47:32,919
Yes, I'm fine.
I hope you'll be very happy.

1680
01:47:32,993 --> 01:47:35,826
Oh, we will be,
all of us.

1681
01:47:37,831 --> 01:47:40,493
What is it, darling?
Tell me.

1682
01:47:40,567 --> 01:47:43,001
I'm very tired.
Good night, Mother.

1683
01:47:45,572 --> 01:47:47,506
Good night, dear.

1684
01:47:56,950 --> 01:47:58,884
[Sobs]

1685
01:48:06,226 --> 01:48:10,629
You know, Annie,
last night when I told
Susie the news,

1686
01:48:12,132 --> 01:48:14,464
she was like ice.

1687
01:48:14,534 --> 01:48:18,402
It's strange.
l... I thought she
would be ecstatic.

1688
01:48:20,907 --> 01:48:24,468
She always seemed to...
To adore Steve.

1689
01:48:28,114 --> 01:48:31,515
Something's wrong
with her, Annie.

1690
01:48:31,585 --> 01:48:33,519
Do you know what it is?

1691
01:48:35,355 --> 01:48:40,657
Miss Lora, you've got
to be very careful
the way you handle Susie.

1692
01:48:40,727 --> 01:48:43,662
She's got
a real problem.
Problem?

1693
01:48:43,730 --> 01:48:47,166
Why don't I know about it?
Why didn't she come to me?

1694
01:48:47,234 --> 01:48:49,828
Maybe because
you weren't around.

1695
01:48:51,171 --> 01:48:53,867
You mean, l...

1696
01:48:53,940 --> 01:48:55,874
I haven't been
a good mother.

1697
01:48:55,942 --> 01:48:58,843
I know you meant
to be a good mother,

1698
01:48:58,912 --> 01:49:01,142
the best kind of mother,

1699
01:49:01,214 --> 01:49:05,947
but look, I meant to
be a good one too,
and I failed.

1700
01:49:06,019 --> 01:49:09,386
But you couldn't have been
a better mother to Sarah Jane.

1701
01:49:09,456 --> 01:49:13,722
- Then where's
my little girl?
- But Annie, that's different.

1702
01:49:13,793 --> 01:49:16,125
Hers is
a very real problem.

1703
01:49:16,196 --> 01:49:18,221
What's complicated
Susie's life?

1704
01:49:18,298 --> 01:49:21,631
We made a home for her;
the prettiest clothes;
the best schools.

1705
01:49:21,701 --> 01:49:25,728
- Susie's in love.
- Oh, Annie.

1706
01:49:25,805 --> 01:49:28,740
Is that all?
Why didn't you say so?

1707
01:49:28,808 --> 01:49:31,936
<i>It's not unusual for a girl</i>
<i>Susie's age to be in love. </i>

1708
01:49:32,012 --> 01:49:35,504
It's who she's in love with
that's causing all the trouble.

1709
01:49:35,582 --> 01:49:39,211
Why? Who is it?

1710
01:49:40,287 --> 01:49:42,221
Mr. Steve.

1711
01:49:44,257 --> 01:49:46,748
What?

1712
01:49:46,826 --> 01:49:49,260
That's impossible.

1713
01:49:49,329 --> 01:49:52,093
How did it happen?
Why did he let it happen?

1714
01:49:52,165 --> 01:49:54,429
I don't think he knows.

1715
01:49:54,501 --> 01:49:56,901
Annie, it can't
be serious!

1716
01:49:56,970 --> 01:49:59,996
It is, Miss Lora.
Plenty serious.

1717
01:50:00,073 --> 01:50:03,008
I better have a talk
with Susie right now.

1718
01:50:03,076 --> 01:50:05,169
Wait, wait.
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

1719
01:50:05,245 --> 01:50:08,339
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

1720
01:50:08,415 --> 01:50:10,542
Susie.

1721
01:50:10,617 --> 01:50:12,744
I've just spoken
to Annie.
Have you?

1722
01:50:12,819 --> 01:50:16,152
Now I know why you were
so upset last night.
So Annie told you.

1723
01:50:16,222 --> 01:50:19,714
That's how you usually
find things out about me.
That's not true!

1724
01:50:19,793 --> 01:50:22,660
Let's face it, Mama.
Annie's always been more
like a real mother.

1725
01:50:22,729 --> 01:50:26,187
You never had time for me.
By the way, is this
worded correctly?

1726
01:50:29,502 --> 01:50:32,164
An application
to college?
Uh-huh.

1727
01:50:32,238 --> 01:50:34,729
But you're going
to study in New York.

1728
01:50:34,808 --> 01:50:37,106
Denver...
It's 1,500 miles away.

1729
01:50:37,177 --> 01:50:39,338
1,628, to be exact.
That's quite a distance.

1730
01:50:39,412 --> 01:50:42,609
I don't think
I'll be missed.
Don't be unfair, Susie.

1731
01:50:42,682 --> 01:50:45,515
You know I'd miss you.
I'm sure you'd be too busy
to miss anyone.

1732
01:50:45,585 --> 01:50:47,576
Much too busy.

1733
01:50:47,654 --> 01:50:49,918
You give me credit
for nothing.

1734
01:50:49,990 --> 01:50:52,788
Yes, I'm ambitious,
perhaps too ambitious,

1735
01:50:52,859 --> 01:50:55,350
but it's been for your sake
as well as mine.

1736
01:50:55,428 --> 01:50:58,363
Isn't this house
just a little bit nicer
than a cold-water flat?

1737
01:50:58,431 --> 01:51:00,865
And your new horse.
Aren't you crazy about it?
Yes, but l...

1738
01:51:00,934 --> 01:51:04,131
And that closet of yours...
Has all the dresses fit for
the daughter of a famous star.

1739
01:51:04,204 --> 01:51:06,138
Now, just a moment,
young lady.

1740
01:51:06,206 --> 01:51:09,471
It's only because
of my ambition that you've
had the best of everything.

1741
01:51:09,542 --> 01:51:12,773
That's a solid achievement
that any mother can be proud of.

1742
01:51:12,846 --> 01:51:14,780
How about a mother's love?

1743
01:51:14,848 --> 01:51:18,045
Love? But you've
always had that!

1744
01:51:18,118 --> 01:51:20,814
Yes, by telephone, postcard,
magazine interviews.

1745
01:51:20,887 --> 01:51:24,050
You've given me everything
but yourself.

1746
01:51:24,124 --> 01:51:28,788
No wonder I went to Annie
last night when I told her
about Steve.

1747
01:51:28,862 --> 01:51:30,796
Oh, Susie.

1748
01:51:33,967 --> 01:51:36,401
If Steve is going
to come between us,

1749
01:51:38,705 --> 01:51:40,900
I'll give him up.

1750
01:51:40,974 --> 01:51:43,135
I'll never see him again.

1751
01:51:43,209 --> 01:51:45,905
Oh, Mama, stop acting!

1752
01:51:45,979 --> 01:51:49,346
Stop trying to shift people
around as if they were pawns
on a stage.

1753
01:51:49,416 --> 01:51:51,850
But, Susie, l...
Don't worry,
I'll get over Steve,

1754
01:51:51,918 --> 01:51:54,352
but please,
don't play the martyr.

1755
01:51:59,025 --> 01:52:03,462
Oh, Mama, I'm sorry.
I didn't want to hurt you.

1756
01:52:03,530 --> 01:52:07,364
But last night
I was so unhappy!
[Sobbing]

1757
01:52:08,935 --> 01:52:10,869
Oh, darling.

1758
01:52:12,505 --> 01:52:15,338
l... I don't know.

1759
01:52:15,408 --> 01:52:18,036
Maybe it was all
to the good because...

1760
01:52:18,111 --> 01:52:22,047
this morning I felt
strangely independent and...

1761
01:52:22,115 --> 01:52:24,549
Well, I like the feeling.

1762
01:52:24,617 --> 01:52:27,609
That's why I think I'd...
I'd like to go away,

1763
01:52:27,687 --> 01:52:29,746
at least for a while.

1764
01:52:29,823 --> 01:52:32,485
Oh, Mama, please try
to understand.

1765
01:52:32,559 --> 01:52:34,493
I'm very sincere
about it.

1766
01:52:38,298 --> 01:52:41,233
Ah, it's funny
the way things turn out.

1767
01:52:46,305 --> 01:52:48,239
Thank you.

1768
01:52:54,747 --> 01:52:57,682
I still can't get over Susie
at the station yesterday.

1769
01:52:57,750 --> 01:53:01,379
She looked so... grown-up
when she said good-bye.

1770
01:53:01,453 --> 01:53:03,387
Yes, she did.

1771
01:53:06,759 --> 01:53:10,195
It does seem awfully
quiet here without her.

1772
01:53:10,262 --> 01:53:12,628
Annie and I were talking
about that last night.

1773
01:53:12,698 --> 01:53:17,101
With both the girls gone,
we felt so alone
in this big house.

1774
01:53:17,169 --> 01:53:19,797
When did this idea
of college come up?

1775
01:53:19,872 --> 01:53:22,306
Susie never once
mentioned it to me.

1776
01:53:22,374 --> 01:53:25,366
She decided suddenly.

1777
01:53:25,444 --> 01:53:28,470
And why Colorado?
So far away.

1778
01:53:28,547 --> 01:53:31,209
It's what she wanted.

1779
01:53:31,283 --> 01:53:34,218
Miss Meredith, it's Annie.
She's terribly sick.

1780
01:53:34,286 --> 01:53:36,880
Did you call
the doctor?
Yes, he'll
be right over.

1781
01:53:36,955 --> 01:53:39,150
And she wants
the minister too.

1782
01:53:47,132 --> 01:53:49,066
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

1783
01:53:58,477 --> 01:54:00,672
Oh, God, no!

1784
01:54:03,015 --> 01:54:05,245
I hate to dispute you,
Miss Lora.

1785
01:54:08,354 --> 01:54:10,288
Oh, Annie, don't talk.

1786
01:54:10,356 --> 01:54:13,018
<i>I've got to talk. </i>
<i>I've got to. </i>
Oh, please.

1787
01:54:13,092 --> 01:54:15,026
Please, not now.

1788
01:54:15,094 --> 01:54:17,028
You stop crying.
But l...

1789
01:54:17,096 --> 01:54:20,862
No, listen to me.
All right.
I'm listening.

1790
01:54:20,933 --> 01:54:23,993
When my bills
are all paid,

1791
01:54:24,069 --> 01:54:27,436
I want everything
that's left to go to...

1792
01:54:27,506 --> 01:54:30,031
Sarah Jane.
Of course.

1793
01:54:30,109 --> 01:54:34,045
Mr. Steve?
<i>Yes, Annie? </i>

1794
01:54:34,113 --> 01:54:37,742
[Breathing Hard]
Find her, Mr. Steve.
Find her.

1795
01:54:37,816 --> 01:54:40,478
I will.
You may be sure.

1796
01:54:40,552 --> 01:54:43,282
<i>I will. </i>
Thank you.

1797
01:54:43,355 --> 01:54:46,256
Miss Lora,
just tell her...

1798
01:54:46,325 --> 01:54:49,726
Tell her I know
I was selfish,

1799
01:54:49,795 --> 01:54:53,492
and if I loved her too much,
I'm sorry.

1800
01:54:54,800 --> 01:54:57,496
But I didn't mean
to cause her any trouble.

1801
01:54:57,569 --> 01:54:59,503
She was all I had.

1802
01:54:59,571 --> 01:55:02,233
<i>Tell her, Miss Lora. </i>
Oh, please, Annie!

1803
01:55:02,307 --> 01:55:05,743
Promise me?
Promise me?
I promise.

1804
01:55:05,811 --> 01:55:08,177
Ohh.

1805
01:55:08,247 --> 01:55:11,080
<i>My pearl necklace. </i>
Yes?

1806
01:55:12,418 --> 01:55:15,319
I want you to give it
to Susie...

1807
01:55:15,387 --> 01:55:17,321
for her weddin'.

1808
01:55:18,624 --> 01:55:21,593
Give her a real
bridey wedding...

1809
01:55:21,660 --> 01:55:23,594
with all the fixin's.

1810
01:55:24,930 --> 01:55:28,024
Our weddin' day...

1811
01:55:28,100 --> 01:55:31,866
and the day we die...

1812
01:55:31,937 --> 01:55:33,871
are the great events...

1813
01:55:35,174 --> 01:55:37,267
of life.

1814
01:55:38,377 --> 01:55:40,311
[Sobbing]
Oh, Annie!

1815
01:55:40,379 --> 01:55:42,506
Annie, darling.

1816
01:55:42,581 --> 01:55:45,846
[Sobbing Continues]
There's no cause to cry.

1817
01:55:45,918 --> 01:55:47,818
- Reverend?
- Yes, Annie?

1818
01:55:51,390 --> 01:55:55,986
I'd like for your wife
to have my fur scarf.

1819
01:55:56,061 --> 01:55:59,724
She always admired
that fur.

1820
01:55:59,798 --> 01:56:04,531
She never believed me when
I said it was genuine mink.

1821
01:56:04,603 --> 01:56:07,333
She did, Annie,
she did.

1822
01:56:07,406 --> 01:56:09,772
Oh, please,
you don't have to...

1823
01:56:09,842 --> 01:56:12,037
And I want Mr. McKinney...

1824
01:56:12,110 --> 01:56:15,944
to have a nice, clean
50-dollar bill.

1825
01:56:16,014 --> 01:56:18,312
M-Mr. McKinney?

1826
01:56:18,383 --> 01:56:22,444
The milkman at the old
cold-water flat.
Oh.

1827
01:56:22,521 --> 01:56:26,617
He was so nice
and understanding
about the bill.

1828
01:56:26,692 --> 01:56:29,718
I always send him
a little something
at Christmas time,

1829
01:56:29,795 --> 01:56:31,729
in both our names.

1830
01:56:33,765 --> 01:56:36,233
You've been so good.

1831
01:56:36,301 --> 01:56:39,498
Sure hope you're right,
Miss Lora.

1832
01:56:39,571 --> 01:56:42,563
I'd like to be standin'
with the lambs...

1833
01:56:42,641 --> 01:56:44,632
and not with the goats...

1834
01:56:44,710 --> 01:56:46,575
on judgment day.

1835
01:56:48,180 --> 01:56:51,013
And my funeral...

1836
01:56:51,083 --> 01:56:53,779
Mr. Steve,

1837
01:56:53,852 --> 01:56:58,312
you'll find what I want
in the drawer...

1838
01:56:58,390 --> 01:57:00,324
over there.

1839
01:57:05,998 --> 01:57:07,932
I've got it, Annie.

1840
01:57:08,000 --> 01:57:10,662
I want to go...

1841
01:57:10,736 --> 01:57:13,569
the way I planned,

1842
01:57:13,639 --> 01:57:17,200
especially
the four white horses...

1843
01:57:17,276 --> 01:57:20,211
and a band playin'.

1844
01:57:20,279 --> 01:57:22,577
No mourning,

1845
01:57:22,648 --> 01:57:26,550
but proud
and high-steppin',

1846
01:57:27,686 --> 01:57:29,916
like I was goin'
to glory.

1847
01:57:29,988 --> 01:57:32,821
No. I won't listen.

1848
01:57:32,891 --> 01:57:36,383
There isn't going
to be any funeral,
not for a long, long time.

1849
01:57:36,461 --> 01:57:39,430
You can't leave me.
I won't let you.

1850
01:57:40,933 --> 01:57:43,401
I'm just tired, Miss Lora.

1851
01:57:45,470 --> 01:57:49,167
Awfully... tired.

1852
01:57:53,412 --> 01:57:55,505
Annie!

1853
01:57:55,581 --> 01:57:58,516
Annie!
[Sobbing]

1854
01:57:58,584 --> 01:58:00,518
No!

1855
